A. opacum.text: Ambystoma cingulatum is one of the only Ambystoma species, other than A. opacum, that courts terrestrially (Petranka 1998).

A. pallidus.text: Individuals of A. pallidus in the wild have been known to live for at least nine years and captive populations have had individuals live for up to eleven years.

A. perideraion.text: While little research has actually been done on the reproductive mechanisms of A. perideraion, a similar species Ampiprion ocellaris showed several interesting reproductive mechanisms.

A. philippii.text: The longevity of A. philippii is unknown but may be similar to A. gazella, in which expected life span is 13 years for males, with females typically living about 23 years. (UNEP World Conservation Monitoring Center, 2001)

A. pusillus.text: There is little available information for A. pusillus concerning their lifespan or longevity.

A. roseicollis.text: The typical lifespan in captivity of A. roseicollis is 15 to 25 years.

A. sayanus.text: It was first suggested that the migration of the anus in A. sayanus was to facilitate gill brooding of its eggs, as is found in northern cavefishes (Amblyopsis spelaea) with similar morphological features.

A. sexdens.text: Although no one has yet observed the complete Atta sexdens mating process, it is theorized that A. sexdens queens are polyandrous.

A. sponsa.text: The average lifespan of A. sponsa is three or four years.

A. swainsonii.text: A. swainsonii develop slowly and are fully mature around 8 months, near the beginning of the next breeding season.

A. virgo.text: The lifespan of A. virgo in the wild is unknown presently.

A.varius.text: A.varius reproduces mostly along streams and other sources of moving water.

Abrocoma cinerea.text: Very little is known about reproduction in Abrocoma cinerea.

Acanthuridae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Acerodon jubatus.text: No information is currently available on longevity in Acerodon jubatus.

Acipenser fulvescens.text: Acipenser fulvescens become sexually mature when they are around the age of twenty and at a length of a little over a meter.

Actinia equina.text: The humoral and cellular immune response to a lipid attenuated pore-forming toxin from the sea anemone Actinia equina L.The immunogenicity of a pore-forming polypeptide, equinatoxin II, from the sea anemone Actinia equina was studied after attenuation of the toxin's lethal and cytolytic activity by autologous polar lipids.

Aechmophorus occidentalis.text: Aechmophorus occidentalis breeds in the spring.

Agapornis roseicollis.text: Agapornis roseicollis shows variability in both nest choice and nest usage.

Agkistrodon piscivorous.text: Little information has been documented on the lifespan of Agkistrodon piscivorous in captivity or in the wild, however, the oldest cottonmouth known lived to 24.5 years old.

Ailurops ursinus.text: It is unknown at what age Ailurops ursinus reaches developmental maturity.

Aiptasia pallida.text: Aiptasia pallida reproduces aesexually and there is no parental investment.

Akodon.text: Young are weaned at about 14 days old in other Akodon species.

Akodon cursor.text: There is little information on mating in Akodon cursor.

Akodon montensis.text: Akodon cursor will occasionally hybridize with other species of the same genus including Akodon montensis.

Alasmidonta marginata.text: Alasmidonta marginata is a long-term brooder.

Alasmidonta viridis.text: Alasmidonta viridis is a long-term brooder.

Alcedo atthis.text: Mating is the only time that Alcedo atthis individuals are not solitary.

Alcedo meninting.text: Polygamy is known to occur in at least one species of kingfisher; male common kingfishers (Alcedo meninting) in Russia frequently breed with up to three females.

Allactodipus bobrinskii.text: Allactodipus bobrinskii has two observed breeding seasons: April to June and September to October.

Amandava amandava.text: The eggs of Amandava amandava are incubated by both parents during the day.

Ametrida centurio.text: Reproduction in Ametrida centurio is not well understood.

Antechinus swainsonii.text: Females of the species Antechinus swainsonii usually die after rearing their first litter and males die shortly after copulation (Williams and Williams 1982).

Anthus spragueii.text: Little is known about the mating systems of Anthus spragueii.

Aonyx cinerea.text: Aonyx cinerea has an estruous cycle that lasts between 22.4 and 30 days, and an estrus of 3 days.

Aotus nancymaae.text: Aotus nancymaae mate year round, but it is speculated that offspring are conceived dependent of the availability of resources.

Aotus nigriceps.text: Not much is known about longevity in Aotus nigriceps in the wild.

Apalone ferox.text: The average and maximum lifespan of Apalone ferox in the wild appears to be unknown.

Apis mellifera.text: Apis mellifera queens usually live 2 to 3 years, but some have been known to last for 5 years.

Aplysia californica.text: Hemolymph of the marine mollusc, Aplysia californica, contains four large particles: acetylcholinesterase, hemocyanin, a hemagglutinin, and a structure tentatively identified as erythrocurorin.

Aptenodytes patagonicus.text: Using oesophageal temperature, we present here a new method for detecting the timing of prey ingestion in free-ranging sea birds, and, to our knowledge, report the first data obtained on king penguins (Aptenodytes patagonicus).

Apus apus.text: The longest living known individuals are: an alpine swift (Tachymarptis melba) of 26 years, a common swift (Apus apus) of 21 years, and a chimney swift (Chaetura pelagica) of 14 years. (Campbell and Lack, 1985; Chantler and Driessens, 2000; Chantler, 1999; Collins, 2001)

Aquila clanga.text: After measuring the gestation period of the closely related species, lesser spotted eagles (Aquila pomarina), experts estimate the gestation period for Aquila clanga to be about six weeks.

Aquila pomarina.text: After measuring the gestation period of the closely related species, lesser spotted eagles (Aquila pomarina), experts estimate the gestation period for Aquila clanga to be about six weeks.

Ara macao.text: Breeding in Ara macao occurs about every one to two years.

Ara maracana.text: The wild male is paired with a female Illiger's macaw (Ara maracana)- a bird of a different species.

Aramus guarauna.text: Not much is known about the breeding habits of Aramus guarauna.

Araneus diadematus.text: The internal reproductive organs of the Araneus diadematus resembles those of other arthopods.

Arapaima gigas.text: Due to the geographic range that Arapaima gigas inhabits, the animal's life cycle is greatly affected by the seasonal flooding that occurs.

Aratinga nana.text: Aratinga nana breed one time during the spring between April and May.

Architeuthis.text: The reproduction of Architeuthis is not well known.

Arctocephalus australis.text: Uruguayan study showed a significant difference in pregnancy rates in Arctocephalus australis from year to year, indicating that both environmental and demographic stochasticity play a role in population dynamics.

Arctocephalus forsteri.text: Arctocephalus forsteri females reach sexual maturity between 4 and 6 years of age, and males become sexually mature near 5-6 years old.

Arctocephalus pusillus.text: The breeding season for both subspecies of Arctocephalus pusillus begins in the middle of October.

Arctocephalus townsendi.text: Unlike most other seal species, the males of Arctocephalus townsendi occasionally observe their harems from the water.

Arctonyx collaris.text: Other badgers (Meles meles and Arctonyx collaris) breed annually.

Argonauta nodosa.text: The female Argonauta nodosa is only able to mate once in her lifetime, whereas the male is able to reproduce multiple times.

Argusianus argus.text: Some gallinaceous birds may live for five to eight years (grouse) in the wild and others may survive up to 30 years in captivity (great argus (Argusianus argus)). (Campbell and Lack, 1985; Delacour and Amadon, 1973; Johnsgard, 1983)

Arion ater.text: Although Arion ater are hermaphroditic, they do engage in cross-fertilization when a mate is available.

Armadillidium vulgare.text: Armadillidium vulgare reproduce on land as opposed to in water.

Artemia salina.text: Parthenogenesis, or reproduction without fertilization, is also common among Artemia salina, particularly in Europe.

Arvicanthis niloticus.text: Arvicanthis niloticus is capable of breeding year-round under highly favorable conditions.

Arvicola terrestris.text: Arvicola terrestris undergoes one mating season per year, usually ranging from early spring (April/March) to late summer/early autumn (August/October).

Asellia tridens.text: The mating system of Asellia tridens has yet to be studied in much detail.

Aspidogaster.text: There have been no documented cases of Aspidogaster directly infecting a vertebrate host as a free egg or larva, while they have been found in the intestines of fish, so it is assumed that vertebrates are infected by ingestion of parasitized mollusks. Aspidobothreans are able to either self-fertilize or mate with another individual. (Bakker and Davids, 1973; Huehner and Etges, 1977; Rohde, 1972; Rohde, 1998)

Aspidogaster conchicola.text: Aspidogaster conchicola usually develops within mollusks, but is a facultative parasite of vertebrates, should their mollusk host be eaten.

Asterias rubens.text: These eggs develop into bipinnaria larvae in the Asterias rubens.

Asterias vulgaris.text: The breeding season of the Asterias vulgaris occurs in the spring.

Astronotus ocellatus.text: Though they can become much larger, Astronotus ocellatus are sexually mature soon in life, usually by the time they are 12 cm long.

Atelerix albiventris.text: Atelerix albiventris generally breeds once or twice a year.

Ateles geoffroyi.text: Ateles geoffroyi does not appear to have a regular breeding season.

Ateles hybridus.text: Similar to the other species of spider monkeys, Ateles hybridus is characterised by a slow reproductive rate, with females usually giving birth to a single offspring every 3 to 4 years.

Atherurus africanus.text: No information was found concerning the gestation period of this species, but the related Atherurus africanus has a pregnancy that lasts 100 to 110 days.

Atherurus macrourus.text: However, not much is known about the lifespan of Atherurus macrourus in the wild.

Atlides halesus.text: Male Atlides halesus will wait on treetops or hilltops from noon to untill sundown (earlier on colder days) for a female to fly by.

Atriplex.text: Young appear above ground at the peak of Atriplex growth, when this plant has its highest water content.

Atta sexdens.text: The eggs, larvae, and pupae of Atta sexdens are generally cared for by gardener-nurse caste workers, with some help from the within-nest specialists if the larvae or pupae are extremely large.

Aurelia aurita.text: Sexual maturity in Aurelia aurita commonly occurs in the spring and summer.

Aurelia labiata.text: The zygotes of Aurelia labiata, called planulae, are brooded on the jelly's manubrium.

Axis porcinus.text: It is not known how many males a female Axis porcinus will allow to mate with her during a given breeding season. Sexual maturity in Axis porcinus occurs at 8-12 months of age.

Aythya americana.text: After that time they begin to spend less time defending the nesting area from predators, other canvasbacks, and Aythya americana.

B. albicauda.text: Virtually nothing is known about the reproductive ecology of B. albicauda or its cousin B. villosa.

B. arnuxii.text: Like all mammals, females B. arnuxii invest heavily in their young through gestation and lactation.

B. canorus.text: B. canorus is a long living species.

B. fervidus.text: Most B. fervidus do not live more than just a few months because of the toll that their work takes on their bodies.

B. gabbii.text: Not much is known about longevity in B. gabbii.

B. gabii.text: Breeding in B. gabii is reported to be aseasonal.

B. gaimardi.text: As in other macropods, B. gaimardi embryos experience a pause in development between fertilization and implantation.

B. klaasi.text: Male B. klaasi sometimes show an interesting post-mating behavior.

B. lesueur.text: There is little information on the lifespan of B. lesueur, but it is known to usually live three years in the wild.

B. torquatus.text: Young B. torquatus weigh approximately 300 grams at birth and cling to the mother for the first 6 to 9 months of life.

B. villosa.text: Virtually nothing is known about the reproductive ecology of B. albicauda or its cousin B. villosa.

Bacopa monniera.text: Eggs are laid singly near or on the underside of leaves of the host plant Bacopa monniera.

Balaena mysticetus.text: cetacea are especially long-lived; 116-year-old fin whales (Balaenoptera physalus) have been reported from the wild and bowhead whales (Balaena mysticetus) may live up to 200 years. (Carey and Judge, 2002; George et al., 1999)

Balaenoptera acutorostrata.text: The milk of their close relatives, common minke whales (Balaenoptera acutorostrata), contains lactose and several other oligosaccharides, some of which have never been found in any other mammalian species.

Balaenoptera acutorostratus.text: The generation time is estimated to be about 22 years. Antarctic minke whales, like Balaenoptera acutorostratus, have a gestation period of 10 months, after which a single young is born at about 2.7 meters long.

Balaenoptera bonaerensis.text: Kasamatsu et al. (1995) found that minke whales (probably Balaenoptera bonaerensis) migrate far north but their main breeding areas are probably between 10º and 20º S.

Balaenoptera physalus.text: cetacea are especially long-lived; 116-year-old fin whales (Balaenoptera physalus) have been reported from the wild and bowhead whales (Balaena mysticetus) may live up to 200 years. (Carey and Judge, 2002; George et al., 1999)

Balistidae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Bartholomea annulata.text: Bartholomea annulata exhibits a biannual reproductive cycle.

Bassariscus sumichrasti.text: The lifespan of - Bassariscus sumichrasti -has not been studied in the wild, but captive animals are known to reach 23 years of age (Poglayen-Neuwall 1989).

Bathygobius soporator.text: Male Bathygobius soporator have also been observed making a knocking sound to initiate courtship.

Bdeogale nigripes.text: Bdeogale nigripes have 1 young per litter.

Berardius arnuxii.text: Little is known about the mating and reproductive habits of Berardius arnuxii.

Berardius bairdii.text: Most Berardius bairdii reach sexual maturity when they are about 9.4 meters long for males and 10 meters long for females.

Bettongia gaimardi.text: Bettongia gaimardi is believed to be polygynous and to breed continuously, however, harsh environment conditions may limit breeding in the wild. ("Parks and Wildlife Services Tasmania", 2003; "Parks and Wildlife Services Tasmania", 2004; "Tasmanian Bettong", 2003; Fisher, Owens, and Johnson, 2001; Rose, 1986; Rose, 1997)

Bettongia penicillata.text: In Bettongia penicillata, bredding is continuous (Christensen 1983).

Bitis nasicornis.text: Bitis nasicornis is a viviparous animal, giving birth to 6-35 young, at the start of the rainy season, (March - April).

Blarina hylophaga.text: Blarina hylophaga is usually solitary, but individuals come together from early spring to early autumn in order to reproduce.

Blatta orientalis.text: The female of the species Blatta orientalis produces from one to eighteen red/brown egg cases during her life: about one case per month.

Bolbometopon muricatum.text: Subsequently, the largest scarid, Bolbometopon muricatum, is the one exception to the 20 year maximum age. (Choat and Robertson, 2002; Choat and Bellwood, 1998)

Bolomys lasiurus.text: Although Bolomys lasiurus is fairly well studied, the lifespan of this mouse is unknown.

Bombina orientalis.text: Bombina orientalis larvae hatch 3 to 10 days after egg laying.

Bombus fervidus.text: Bombus fervidus queens care for their first brood themselves, while later generations are cared for by workers.

Bombycilla cedrorum.text: This species breeds later than most birds, even later than their close relatives, cedar waxwings (Bombycilla cedrorum).

Bombyx mori.text: Bombyx mori spend 2 weeks as pupae in the safety of their cocoons before emerging as adults (Encarta 1998).

Bonasa umbellus.text: This species is also known to lay eggs in the nests of Bonasa umbellus.

Bos frontalis.text: Though lifespan has not been studied in the wild, one captive Bos frontalis lived to be 26 years of age (Nowak 1999).

Bos grunniens.text: The mating season for Bos grunniens starts in September, with births usually occuring in June (Buchholtz, 1990). In the wild, the female Bos grunniens have one calf every other year.

Bos taurus.text: Young Bos taurus are preocial, they learn to recognize their mother and are able to stand and walk soon after birth.

Brachypelma klaasi.text: The female Brachypelma klaasi lays a single egg sac containing 400 to 800 eggs in her burrow in April to May, immediately before the first rains of the season.

Bradypus tridactylus.text: Bradypus tridactylus mates high in the safety of the trees.

Brychius hungerfordi.text: In the spring and early summer months, Brychius hungerfordi probably lays eggs on filamentous algae and aquatic plants.

Bubalus mindorensis.text: Bubalus mindorensis breeds during the dry season, from December to May.

Bubalus quarlesi.text: Although Bubalus quarlesi are usually solitary animals, they will form a herd when cows are about to give birth.

Bubo virginianus.text: Predation by great horned owls (Bubo virginianus) leads to deaths as well.

Bufo boreas.text: Bufo canorus have been known to hybridize with Bufo boreas in the northern parts of their range.

Bufo canorus.text: Bufo canorus have been known to hybridize with Bufo boreas in the northern parts of their range.

Bufo fowleri.text: Breeding habits of Bufo fowleri are very similar to Bufo americanus.

Buteo buteo.text: Pairs sometimes find nests on the ground or use deserted nests of other larger bird species (such as Buteo buteo (common buzzard) or Pica pica (black-billed magpie)), which can be located in trees or on high ledges.

Pica pica.text: Pairs sometimes find nests on the ground or use deserted nests of other larger bird species (such as Buteo buteo (common buzzard) or Pica pica (black-billed magpie)), which can be located in trees or on high ledges.

Bufo americanus.text: Breeding habits of Bufo fowleri are very similar to Bufo americanus.

Bufo marinus.text: Bufo marinus is able to reproduce nearly year round.

Bufo terrestris.text: Bufo terrestris spends 30-55 days as a tadpole before metamorphasing upon attaining a length between 6.5-11mm (Wright 1949).

Bunolagus monticularis.text: Little is known about the life cycle of Bunolagus monticularis.

Burramys parvus.text: The inactive season, from May-September, is hibernation season for Burramys parvus.

Buteo.text: Both the incubation and fledging periods are longer than other Buteo species.

Buteo brachyurus.text: Buteo brachyurus normally lays two eggs, although clutch size varies from one to three eggs.

Buteo lagopus.text: Buteo lagopus will usually migrate solo (very uncommon to fly in groups) and find a mate once they have reached their destination.

Butorides striata.text: While information regarding longevity of lava herons is scarce, the oldest known wild individuals from the same genus are recorded at 7.9 years for Butorides striata and 11.6 years Butorides virescens.

Butorides virescens.text: While information regarding longevity of lava herons is scarce, the oldest known wild individuals from the same genus are recorded at 7.9 years for Butorides striata and 11.6 years Butorides virescens.

Bycanistes subcylindricus.text: Bycanistes subcylindricus individuals commonly nest in naturally formed cavities 9 to 30 m high in large (>3 m circumference) rainforest trees.

C. Walie.text: The typical mating system in C. Walie is polygyny, with dominant males siring a disproportionate amount of offspring during the breeding season.

C. alba.text: The breeding season of C. alba is dependent on the weather.

C. apella.text: Typical longevity in the wild is unknown, but captive C. apella may live to 45 years old.

C. ascanius.text: It is likely that C. ascanius is similar to other members of the genus in lifespan.

C. auritus.text: It is thought that C. auritus take care of their young until they are able to survive on their own.

C. baileyi.text: It is likely that C. baileyi is similar, and that the young become independent of the mother shortly after this age.

C. bailwardi.text: The only studies done on C. bailwardi have been in captivity, so the lifespan in the wild is not known.

C. brachyotis.text: Reproduction in C. brachyotis is timed so that lactation corresponds with the peak of the rainy season--which is the fruiting season.

C. brevicaudata.text: Since C. lanigera and C. brevicaudata are closely related, one may infer that the estrus cycles are similar.

C. brevis.text: The female C. brevis lays her eggs in an underground burrow or den.

C. californicus.text: C. californicus typically produce one litter a year (occasionally two) between April and July.

C. calvus.text: The lifespan of the closely related species C. calvus in the wild is about twenty years, which is a likely estimate in age for C. melanocephalus based on the many genetic and environmental similarities between these species (which suggest a similar life history as well as similar sources of extraneous mortality). (Lindenfors, 2002)

C. caracal.text: One hypothesis to explain the breeding habits of C. caracal is the “use” of an opportunistic strategy.

C. caurinus.text: After the eggs have hatched, female C. caurinus begin feeding the hatchlings.

C. centralis.text: No information could be found on the lifespan of C. tatouay, however, a specimen of the closely related C. unicinctus lived seven and a half years in captivity and a C. centralis specimen lived eight years in captivity. (Weigl, 2005)

C. cephus.text: Little is documented about the parental investment of C. cephus, but close relatives of moustached guenons produce young that are relatively well developed at birth with open eyes and the means to support their own weight and embrace their mother.

C. chinga.text: The breedings season for C. chinga is generally in late February.

C. concoveri.text: The condition of C. concoveri at birth has not been reported.

C. conepatus.text: It is reasonable to assume that C. conepatus is similar.

C. conoveri.text: Female C. conoveri are monoestrus, bearing one litter per year.

C. cornuta.text: Little is know about the lifespan of C. cornuta in the wild, but in captivity they have fairly long lives.

C. crocodilus.text: Melanosuchus niger - pods were found to occur in areas of deeper water than -C. crocodilus-, implying choice of nesting sites in lower-lying areas (Britton 1999, Da Silveira et al 1997, Herron 1990, Thorbjarnarson 1998).

C. diabolis.text: The lifespan of C. diabolis is between 6 and 12 months.

C. falconeri.text: The lifespan of C. falconeri ranges from 11 to 13 years.

C. fallax.text: The gestation period for C. fallax is about 24 to 26 days.

C. fuliginosus.text: Information does not exist on the lifespan of C. fuliginosus, partly because of the inaccessible and rugged habitat in which they live.

C. guereza.text: Therefore, SIVcol from guereza colobus monkeys (C. guereza) is the first primate lentivirus identified in the Colobinae subfamily and the divergence of SIVcol may reflect divergence of the host lineage.

C. h. atricaudatus.text: Females are mature at snout to vent lengths of over 100 cm in C. h. atricaudatus and 67 to 90 cm in C. h. horridus. (Ernst and Ernst, 2003)

C. h. horridus.text: Females are mature at snout to vent lengths of over 100 cm in C. h. atricaudatus and 67 to 90 cm in C. h. horridus. (Ernst and Ernst, 2003)

C. hircus.text: Mothers of C. hircus nurse their young for 10 months after birth.

C. hispidus.text: There is little information available about the parental care habits of C. hispidus.

C. kuhlii.text: The dominant female of a group of C. kuhlii mates with several males.

C. l. dingo.text: Pups of C. l. dingo first venture from the natal den at three weeks of age.

C. lanigera.text: Since C. lanigera and C. brevicaudata are closely related, one may infer that the estrus cycles are similar.

C. leucodon.text: The breeding season for C. leucodon runs from March to September with 2 to 4 litters being produced during that time.

C. ludovicianus.text: Female C. ludovicianus who mate do not always produce litters.

C. melanocephalus.text: The lifespan of the closely related species C. calvus in the wild is about twenty years, which is a likely estimate in age for C. melanocephalus based on the many genetic and environmental similarities between these species (which suggest a similar life history as well as similar sources of extraneous mortality). (Lindenfors, 2002)

C. neglectus.text: The longevity of C. neglectus has not been reported, but other species within the genus Cercopithecus have been reported to live in excess of 30 years in captivity.

C. parva.text: One captive C. parva lived for 21 months.

C. pearsoni.text: The lifespan of C. pearsoni is unknown.

C. perlatus.text: Once C. perlatus have found shells, they live on land the rest of their lives.

C. philander.text: The mating system of C. philander is little understood.

C. rudis.text: Sex ratios in C. rudis are biased, with about 79% males, which promotes this helper behavior.

C. satanus.text: All other reproduction information for C. satanus is based on observations of a hybrid born to a female Chiropotes albinasus and a male C. satanas in captivity.

C. schadenbergi.text: There is little information on parental care in C. schadenbergi.

C. sclateri.text: Little is known about parental investment in C. sclateri.

C. sibirica.text: The timing of mating seasons for C. sibirica varies between mountain ranges and is significantly affected by weather conditions.

C. sordidulus.text: Although information on the exact life expectancy of C. sordidulus is unavailable, Contopus virens, which are very similar to western wood-pewee groups, have a life expectancy of about 7 years.

C. talarum.text: Captive C. talarum has an average gestation period of 102 days and a mean litter size of 5 offspring, with a range of between 1 and 7 individuals. (Redford and Eisenberg, 1992)

C. tarsalis.text: In general, C. tarsalis will breed in water in any sunny location, and will tolerate a wide range of water conditions.

C. tatouay.text: There is currently no information available on the parental investment given by C. tatouay, or of related species.

C. taurinus.text: Like C. taurinus, 80-90% of all calves are dropped within the three week birth peak.

C. unicinctus.text: No information could be found on the lifespan of C. tatouay, however, a specimen of the closely related C. unicinctus lived seven and a half years in captivity and a C. centralis specimen lived eight years in captivity. (Weigl, 2005)

C. xanthosternos.text: Though the longest lifespan for C. xanthosternos has not been documented, a similar species, Cebus apella, can live as long as 45 years in captivity. ("Tufted or Brown Capuchin-Cebus Apella", 2009; "Yellow-breasted Capuchin", 2008)

Cabassous centralis.text: Not much research has been done specifically on the reproduction patterns of Cabassous centralis.

Cabassous tatouay.text: Cabassous tatouay gives birth to one offspring per year.

Cacajao calvus.text: However, the lack of the major markers of sexual dimorphism such as large male canine size, the presence of sagittal or nuchal crests, or flamboyant colorings suggests that this species is largely monogamous, as is its sister taxon Cacajao calvus. Breeding appears to be seasonal, as young infants and lactating females have been observed only in the months of March and April, corresponding with the setting of fruit in igapo forests.

Cacatua alba.text: Cacatua alba chicks are born altrical and are completely dependent upon their parents.

Cacatua galerita.text: Both male and female Cacatua galerita reach reproductive maturity around the age of 3 to 4 years. (Cambridge University Press, 1991; Equinox, 1985; Forshaw, 2002)

Caenorhabditis elegans.text: Temperature plays a major role in the development of Caenorhabditis elegans.

Calcarius pictus.text: Smith’s longspurs (Calcarius pictus) are polygynandrous (promiscuous, males and females have multiple mates).

Callicebus cupreus.text: There is little information available on the lifespan of Callicebus cupreus.

Callicebus moloch.text: A related species, Callicebus moloch, has a life span of 25 years. (Johnson, 1996)

Callicebus personatus.text: Longevity of Callicebus personatus is unknown in the wild.

Callimico goeldii.text: The exception to this pattern are Callimico goeldii, which give birth to a single young during the wet season, although births may occur year-round in captivity.

Callithrix.text: Lifespan in the genus Callithrix seems to be about 10 years in the wild and up to 16 years in captivity (Nowak, 1991).

Callithrix aurita.text: Most Callithrix aurita give birth to two young during spring each year.

Callithrix chrysoleuca.text: All four mating systems can be found in one social group of Callithrix chrysoleuca.

Callithrix jacchus.text: Some species (e.g. Callithrix jacchus and Panthera leo) display cooperative breeding, in which groups of females, and sometimes males, share the care of young from one or more females.

Calloplesiops altivelis.text: Male Calloplesiops altivelis protect the egg mass until hatching.

Callosciurus erythraeus.text: However, Callosciurus erythraeus lived 17 years in captivity.

Callosciurus notatus.text: A new digenean, Allassogonoporus callosciuri n. sp. from the plantain squirrel Callosciurus notatus from the Malaysian state of Sarawak, Borneo, is described.

Callosciurus prevosti.text: Callosciurus typically gestate for 40 days and infants weigh about 16 g. The close relative, Callosciurus prevosti reproduces after they are a year old and can have up to 3 litters per year.

Callosciurus prevostii.text: Reports on parental care in Callosciurus prevostii are not available.

Calloscriurus caniceps.text: Vaughan et al. (2000) suggest a related Malaysian tree squirrel species, Calloscriurus caniceps, imitates predator calls to stop movements of the female and other males after copulation.

Caloprymnus campestris.text: Note: Due to indeterminate status (see Conservation and Biodiversity section), some reproductive characters were determined by comparing Caloprymnus campestris to the Rufous Rat kangaroos and other "rat" kangaroos, rather than by direct observation (Ganslosser, 1988).

Calosoma sycophanta.text: Calosoma sycophanta females lay eggs in the spring.

Caluromys derbianus.text: Litter size for Caluromys derbianus is usually three or four, although it may be as high as six.

Caluromys philander.text: Closely related, Caluromys philander individuals have been known to live up to 5 years in captivity and 41 months in the wild.

Calypte anna.text: Male and female Calypte anna only come together to mate.

Calypte costae.text: The breeding season of Calypte costae varies with latitude and habitat, but always takes place between the months of January and May.

Calyptomena viridis.text: Male green broadbills (Calyptomena viridis) have a spinning display; others have displays that involve head bobbing, wing flapping and feather fluffing.

Camelus bactrianus.text: Young Camelus bactrianus are precocial, being able to stand and run soon after birth.

Camelus dromedarius.text: Three isolates of Brucella abortus biovar 3 were recovered out of 38 different samples obtained from free-ranging camels (Camelus dromedarius) in Eastern Sudan.

Cancer irroratus.text: Cancer irroratus reproduction occurs in the autumn.

Canis lupus.text: Coyotes hybridize with Canis lupus familiaris and occasionally with Canis lupus.

Canis lupus familiaris.text: Coyotes hybridize with Canis lupus familiaris and occasionally with Canis lupus.

Canis simensis.text: Data on life expectancy is inadequate, but Canis simensis is likely to live 8-9 years in the wild (Macdonald 1984).

Cannomys badius.text: Female Cannomys badius can bear one to five young per birth (Grzimek, 1990).

Canorus.text: Yosemite toads for songs of spring birds. Canorus means "tuneful" in Latin.

Capra falconeri.text: Capra falconeri breeds annually, with the rut occurring in the autumn and winter months.

Capra ibex.text: Capra ibex, a related species, has been reported to live 10 to 16 years in the wild. (Jordan, 1969; Mendelssohn, 1990)

Capra nubiana.text: The oldest known individual of Capra nubiana lived 17 years in captivity.

Capra pyrenaica.text: The gestation period of Capra pyrenaica is 161-168 days.

Capra walie.text: Capra walie is distinguished from other ibex species in its ability to breed at all times of the year.

Caprimulgus carolinensis.text: There is some competition with related species, such as Caprimulgus carolinensis for territorial space and for food that might impact their longevity. (Cink, 2002)

Caprimulgus vociferus.text: There is no information on how long nestlings or fledglings are dependent on parents, but estimates based on whippoorwills (Caprimulgus vociferus) and nighthawks (Chordeiles minor) suggest young are dependent on parents for about 50 days after hatching.

Capromys pilorides.text: Capromys pilorides, another capromyid found in Cuba, gives birth to fully furred offspring after 110 to 140 days. ("Hutias (Capromyidae)", 2003; Anderson et al., 1983)

Caracal caracal.text: Reliable longevity data for wild Caracal caracal individuals has not been reported.

Caracara cheriway.text: Some of the oldest known falconids include a crested caracara (Caracara cheriway) and a peregrine falcon (Falco peregrinus), both of which lived to 22 years old. ("Falcons and Caracaras (Falconidae)", 2002; Snyder, 2001)

Carcharhinus amblyrhynchos.text: Gray reef sharks mature at 7-7.5 years of age. (Compagno, 1984; Murphy, 1993) Carcharhinus amblyrhynchos females nourish their offspring while they are still inside them, but once the babies are born they are left to feed and protect themselves. (Compagno, 1984)

Cardiocranius paradoxus.text: This is most likely due to the fact that Cardiocranius paradoxus is a rare species, living in isolated areas, and difficult to study.

Cardisoma guanhumi.text: Unfortunately, there is not much further data available regarding the lifespan of Cardisoma guanhumi.

Caretta caretta.text: Peak mating season for Caretta caretta occurs in the early summer months.

Carettochelys insculpta.text: Its nesting habits also seem to resemble some marine turtles in that Carettochelys insculpta is a evening and night nester.

Carpodacus mexicanus.text: Carpodacus mexicanus are known to live up to 11 years and 7 months in the wild, though most probably live much shorter lives.

Castor fiber.text: Castor fiber reaches sexual maturity in 2.5 to 3 years.

Casuarius bennetti.text: Little is known about the mating system of Casuarius bennetti.

Casuarius casuarius.text: However, more research has been completed on a related species, Casuarius casuarius, commonly known as southern cassowaries.

Cebus.text: Infant care is not restricted to the maternal female in Cebus albifrons.

Cebus albifrons.text: Infant care is not restricted to the maternal female in Cebus albifrons.

Cebus apella.text: Though the longest lifespan for C. xanthosternos has not been documented, a similar species, Cebus apella, can live as long as 45 years in captivity. ("Tufted or Brown Capuchin-Cebus Apella", 2009; "Yellow-breasted Capuchin", 2008)

Cebus xanthosternos.text: While young females of the genus Cebus tend to stay within their mother’s group as they age, males usually leave their birth group to join a new one around 2 to 4 years old. ("Capuchins (Subfamily Cebinae)", 1990; Campbell et al., 2007; Kenneth, 2004; Nowak, 1991) Because the mating system of Cebus xanthosternos is likely to be a promiscuous multimale and multifemale system (based on the species’ presumed reproductive similarity to Cebus apella), the paternity of offspring may not always be known.

Cediopsylla simplex.text: The reproductive behavior of Cediopsylla simplex has earned it much attention from the research community.

Celtis timorensis.text: This species is highly selective in the choice of tree species used for nesting, studies of the golf course colony have shown that Terminalia catappa and Celtis timorensis are the preferred species of nesting tree comprising 65.5% of the trees chosen.

Centrostephanus coronatus.text: Juveniles hide in the spines of Centrostephanus coronatus.

Cepalophus niger.text: Anecdotal evidence would indicate that Chinese muntjacs, which are described as a duiker-like (for example, Cepalophus niger) organism due to its rapid development and its generalist tendencies, would probably have a similar life expectancy: 10 to 12 years.

Cephalophus niger.text: There does not seem to be a restricted breeding season in Cephalophus niger.

Cephalorhynchus commersonii.text: Although longevity has not been determined in Chilean dolphins, the related species, Cephalorhynchus commersonii and Cephalorhynchus hectori have a lifespan of up to 20 years. (Brownell and Donovan, 1988)

Cephalorhynchus hectori.text: Cephalorhynchus commersonii and Cephalorhynchus hectori have a lifespan of up to 20 years.

Cephalorhynchus heavisidii.text: There is limited data on the reproduction of Cephalorhynchus heavisidii.

Cercartetus caudatus.text: The gestation period of Cercartetus caudatus is unknown, but young leave the pouch when they are about 45 days old and weigh between 5 and 7 grams.

Cercartetus lepidus.text: Male Cercartetus lepidus have been found with regressed testes and testes that are smaller than normal, suggesting that males may not be reproductively active throughout the year (Ward, 1992).

Cercartetus nanus.text: Like most marsupials, Cercartetus nanus has young that are altricial at birth.

Cercopithecus ascanius.text: Cercopithecus ascanius displays a polygynous-promiscuous mating system (Cords et al., 1984).

Cercopithecus hamlyni.text: The birth season for Cercopithecus hamlyni is from May to October.

Cercopithecus sclateri.text: Cercopithecus sclateri is not known from captivity (one animal at Port Harcourt Zoo, Nigeria) and no ages from the wild have been reported.

Cerdocyon thous.text: The gestation period of Cerdocyon thous averages 56 days, leading to a peak of births in January and February (Nowak, 1999).

Cerianthus lloydii.text: The fertilized eggs of Cerianthus lloydii usually develop into planula larva, that settle and develop into polyps.

Cervus alfredi.text: Information on the parental care of Cervus alfredi is not available.

Cervus elaphus.text: It occurs in species as different as elk (Cervus elaphus) and killer whales (Orcinus orca).

Cervus eldii.text: Cervus eldii females can begin reproducing at 2 years of age and typically continue to reproduce until they are 10 years of age.

Cervus nippon.text: Cervus nippon is polygamous, and a successful male will gather as many as 12 females on his territory over the course of the mating (rutting) season (Feldhamer 1980, Nowak 1991).

Cervus unicolor.text: In captivity, Cervus unicolor can live for over 26 years, but in the wild the average lifespan is about 20 years (Nowak, 1999).

Ceryle alcyon.text: For example, belted kingfishers (Ceryle alcyon) drop dead prey into the water for their young to practice diving.

Chaerephon pumilus.text: The breeding season in Chaerephon pumilus varies by location.

Chaeropus ecaudatus.text: Not much is known about the specifics of Chaeropus ecaudatus reproduction, but a pattern can be inferred from the reproduction of other bandicoots.

Chaetodipus formosus.text: The is no information found on the mating systems of long-tailed pocket mice (Brylski, 1999; Guinn, 2002) Chaetodipus formosus is an iteroparous species breeding more than once in its life time.

Chaetodipus nelsoni.text: Chaetodipus nelsoni breeds seasonally from February to August.

Chaetodipus penicillatus.text: Chaetodipus penicillatus has a high population turnover rate, as high as 95% annually.

Chaetodon aculeatus.text: Spawning pairs in Chaetodon aculeatus have been observed chasing each other around a large sponge.

Chaetodon auriga.text: There is little information available on parental investment of Chaetodon auriga, however other species of butterflyfish do not invest in parental care (Roberts and Ormond, 1992).

Chaetophractus villosus.text: Chaetophractus villosus is born with a soft, leathery skin which hardens with age (Nowak, 1999).

Chaetura pelagica.text: The longest living known individuals are: an alpine swift (Tachymarptis melba) of 26 years, a common swift (Apus apus) of 21 years, and a chimney swift (Chaetura pelagica) of 14 years. (Campbell and Lack, 1985; Chantler and Driessens, 2000; Chantler, 1999; Collins, 2001)

Chaetura vauxi.text: Nest sites are usually in dark places such as caves or hollow trees (Vaux’s swifts (Chaetura vauxi) will nest in the cavities made by pileated woodpeckers (Dryocopus pileatus)).

Chauliodus sloani.text: Like other types of reproductive characteristics, very little information has been gathered in respect to the parental investment of Chauliodus sloani.

Cheirogaleidae.text: Cheirogaleidae are noted to live 15 to 19 years in captivity. Allocebus trichotis is probably similar.

Cheirogaleus major.text: Cheirogaleus major is reported to be solitary, with males demonstrating intolerance for one another.

Cheirogaleus medius.text: A closely related animal, Cheirogaleus medius is reported to have lived nearly 20 years in captivity.

Cheiromeles torquatus.text: Cheiromeles torquatus usually has two offspring.

Chelus fimbriatus.text: Prior to mating, male Chelus fimbriatus will repetitively extend the head toward the female while opening and closing the mouth.

Chen caerulescens.text: The actual lifespan of Chen caerulescens is unknown, however, it is believed they have quite long lifespans.

Chinchilla brevicaudata.text: Females of Chinchilla brevicaudata have a 128 day gestation period and 1-2 litters per year.

Chinchilla lanigera.text: Life span in the wild of Chinchilla lanigera is roughly 10 years, but some domesticated chinchillas have lived for over 20 years. (Nowak 1991, Grzimek 1975)

Chironectes minimus.text: Females of Chironectes minimus are polyestrous.

Chiropotes albinasus.text: Mating has been observed in captivity although it was between a female Chiropotes albinasus and a male Chiropotes satanas, producing a hybrid offspring.

Chiropotes satanas.text: There is little information available on the reproductive cycles of Chiropotes satanas in the wild.

Chlamydosaurus kingii.text: The mating season for Chlamydosaurus kingii corresponds to the wet season, beginning in October or November and lasting until February or March.

Chlamydoselachus anguineus.text: Chlamydoselachus anguineus is an ovoviviparous shark that can bear anywhere from two to twelve live young (Dulvy & Reynolds, 1997).

Chlamyphorus retusus.text: The reproductive behavior of Chlamyphorus retusus has not been studied in great detail because this species is extremely rare and has never bred in captivity.

Chlorocebus aethiops.text: Little is known about the reproductive habits of Chlorocebus aethiops; however, like most primates, they are cyclically receptive.

Choerodon fasciatus.text: Like other Labridae, the mating group of Choerodon fasciatus consists of one male with multiple females (Melbourne Aquarium).

Choeronycteris mexicana.text: Once young can fly, Choeronycteris mexicana may move their roosts to areas of greater food availability.

Choloepus hoffmanni.text: An individual Choloepus didactylus (Linnaeus's two-toed sloth) was still alive after 28 years in captivity and a captive Choloepus hoffmanni lived for 32 years.

Choloepus didactylus.text: An individual Choloepus didactylus (Linnaeus's two-toed sloth) was still alive after 28 years in captivity and a captive Choloepus hoffmanni lived for 32 years.

Chordeiles minor.text: There is no information on how long nestlings or fledglings are dependent on parents, but estimates based on whippoorwills (Caprimulgus vociferus) and nighthawks (Chordeiles minor) suggest young are dependent on parents for about 50 days after hatching.

Chrotogale owstoni.text: Newborn Chrotogale owstoni weigh around 75-88 grams (Nowak 1999).

Chrysops vittatus.text: Little information is available on the exact mating behaviors of Chrysops vittatus.

Ciccaba virgata.text: Ciccaba virgata have smaller clutches than ecologically similar or closely related species.

Cichlidae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Ciconia ciconia.text: Ciconia ciconia remain in life-long monogamous mating pairs from the age of three or four.

Ciconia nigra.text: Ciconia nigra breed annually in late April or May.

Cimex hemipterus.text: Cimex hemipterus prefers spaces built with materials such as wood and paper to stone, plaster, or textiles.

Ciona intestinalis.text: The Ciona intestinalis is hermaphroditic and releases sperm and eggs through the exhalent siphon.

Circus cyaneus.text: North American examples of these species include Circus cyaneus and Rostrhamus sociabilis.

Citrus limon.text: The most common host plants for ruby-spotted swallowtails are Citrus limon and Casimiroa edulis in Mexico.

Casimiroa edulis.text: The most common host plants for ruby-spotted swallowtails are Citrus limon and Casimiroa edulis in Mexico.

Clamator glandarius.text: Breeding: During the early summer, male and female Clamator glandarius can be seen flying and foraging together, often chasing each other and frequently exchanging calls.

Clemmys guttata.text: In this species, the sex of the hatchling is independent of incubation temperature, a departure from the trend in closely related emydid species (such as Clemmys guttata and Emydoidea blandingii) in which embryonic sex differentiation is directly related to nest temperatures during the middle third of the incubation period (Ewert and Nelson, 1991).

Clemmys insculpta.text: Hatchling Clemmys insculpta generally emerge from their nests in late August or September and move to water.

Clethrionomys californicus.text: Clethrionomys californicus construct lichen nests under logs and forest floor debris.

Clistosaccus paguri.text: Upon emergence, Clistosaccus paguri will subsist through a period of nearly 4 months without a mantle aperture.

Clonorchis sinensis.text: Clonorchis sinensis is hermaphroditic therefore every single sexually mature fluke will produce eggs.

Clostridium botulinum.text: Botulism (Clostridium botulinum) and avian cholera (Pasteurella multocida), both bacterial diseases, impact blue-winged teal populations heavily through ingestion of the bacteria.

Clupea harengus.text: Clupea harengus uses external fertilization of eggs.

Clypeaster subdepressus.text: Clypeaster subdepressus is capable of producing gametes throughout the year.

Cnemidophorus sonorae.text: Cnemidophorus sonorae is a unisexual, all-female species that breeds by parthenogenesis (Goldberg et al.

Coccyzus erythropthalmus.text: They may lay eggs in the nest of other yellow-billed cuckoos, or in the nests of other bird species, including Coccyzus erythropthalmus, Turdus americanus, Dumetella carolinensis and Hylocichla mustelina.

Coenobita perlatus.text: Coenobita perlatus can live up to 25-30 years in the wild, but once in captivity they typically live from 1-4 years.

Coereba flaveola.text: Reproduction varies slightly among the subspecies of Coereba flaveola.

Coereba flaveola portoricensis.text: The bananaquit (Coereba flaveola portoricensis), Puerto Rican bullfinch (Loxigilla portoricensis) and Puerto Rican tody (Todus mexicanus) are all birds which share nests with E. coqui.

Colaptes auratus.text: They nest in cavities excavated by Colaptes auratus or in nest boxes.

Colias philodice.text: Females appear not to care about the coloration of the males but ultraviolet reflection must be present, which helps reduce hybridization with yellow sulphurs Colias philodice that lack the reflection.

Colias philodice vitabunda.text: Colias philodice vitabunda flies mainly from June until mid-July.

Colobus polykomos.text: A member of the related species Colobus polykomos is reported to have lived 23.5 years in captivity.

Colobus vellerosus.text: There is relatively little information on reproduction in Colobus vellerosus.

Columbia inca.text: Columbia inca have a typical lifespan of 2-3 years however one banded individual has reached an age of 7 years and 9 months (Mueller, 1992).

Condylura cristata.text: Not much is known about the lifespan of Condylura cristata in the wild.

Conepatus chinga.text: Much is unknown about the lifespan of Conepatus chinga, but recent studies have shed the light on its duration.

Conepatus mesoleucus.text: Data are lacking on the breeding season of this species, but in congeneric Conepatus mesoleucus in Texas, reproduction usually occurs between February and March.

Contia tenuis.text: They originated from at least 50 racers, sharp-tailed snakes (Contia tenuis), ring-necked snakes (Diadophis punctatus), and gopher snakes (Pituophis catenifer) (Greene,1997). (Conant and Collins, 1998; Greene, 1997)

Contopus virens.text: Although information on the exact life expectancy of C. sordidulus is unavailable, Contopus virens, which are very similar to western wood-pewee groups, have a life expectancy of about 7 years.

Copadichromis eucinostomous.text: Some lekking species, such as Copadichromis eucinostomous, migrate inshore and build volcano-like nests out of sand, while others lek in open waters, such as Paracyprichromis brieni.

Paracyprichromis brieni.text: Some lekking species, such as Copadichromis eucinostomous, migrate inshore and build volcano-like nests out of sand, while others lek in open waters, such as Paracyprichromis brieni.

Copella arnoldi.text: Quite an elaborate form of parental care is found in Copella arnoldi.

Cophosaurus texanus.text: The eggs of Cophosaurus texanus are laid from March to August and take about fifty days to hatch (Bartlett and Bartlett 1999).

Coracias garrulus.text: European rollers (Coracias garrulus) live for approximately 8.9 years in captivity. (Mackworth-Praed and Grant, 1970)

Corallus caninus.text: Little is known about Corallus caninus reproduction.

Cordylus cataphractus.text: Cordylus cataphractus is a potentially long lived species, with life spans reaching 20 to 25 years in captivity.

Coris aygula.text: Coris aygula is a member of the wrasse family.

Corvus caurinus.text: Young Corvus caurinus probably reach sexual maturity between 15 and 20 months.

Corvus corax.text: For example, roadrunner eggs have been observed in the nests of the Corvus corax and the Mimus polyglottos.

Mimus polyglottos.text: For example, roadrunner eggs have been observed in the nests of the Corvus corax and the Mimus polyglottos. (Aragon et al., 1999; Kaufman, 1996; Stokes and Stokes, 1996; Youth, 1997)

Corydalus cornutus.text: Corydalus cornutus takes one to three years to complete its life-cycle. (Anderson, 2003; McCafferty, 1983)

Corydon sumatranus.text: Observations have been made of groups of up to twenty dusky broadbills (Corydon sumatranus) building a single nest.

Corynactis californica.text: All Corynactis californica reproduce asexually by fission and budding.

Corynorhinus townsendii.text: It has been noted that the life expectancy of Corynorhinus townsendii is much shorter when kept in captivity. (Barbour and Davis, 1969; de Magalhaes, Costa, and Toussaint, 2005; Gruver and Keinath, 2006)

Coryphella lineata.text: Like all nudibranchs, Coryphella lineata is hermaphroditic.

Coryphopterus personatus.text: Gobies exhibit a wide variety of mating systems but most seem to be promiscuous, either organized into a hierarchical social system, such as Coryphopterus personatus, or small territories maintained by individuals, such as Coryphopterus glaucofrenum and Lythrypnus dalli.

Lythrypnus dalli.text: Gobies exhibit a wide variety of mating systems but most seem to be promiscuous, either organized into a hierarchical social system, such as Coryphopterus personatus, or small territories maintained by individuals, such as Coryphopterus glaucofrenum and Lythrypnus dalli.

Coryphopterus glaucofrenum.text: Gobies exhibit a wide variety of mating systems but most seem to be promiscuous, either organized into a hierarchical social system, such as Coryphopterus personatus, or small territories maintained by individuals, such as Coryphopterus glaucofrenum and Lythrypnus dalli.

Cottidae.text: Lernaeocera branchialis develops into a copepodid, which attaches to an intermediate host, such as a lumpfish (e.g. Cyclopterus lumpus), sculpin (Cottidae), or flounder (Pleuronectidae).

Craspedacusta sowerbyi.text: Craspedacusta sowerbyi reproduce asexually in the polyp form, via budding.

Craterna macphersonae.text: Nudibranchs exhibit both indirect (larval) and direct (larvae absent) development, depending on the species; these data were not available specifically for Craterna macphersonae.

Crax rubra.text: The yellow knob at the base of the bill of great curassows (Crax rubra) increases in size during courtship. (Campbell and Lack, 1985; Delacour and Amadon, 1973; Stiles and Skutch, 1991)

Cricetomys gambianus.text: Litter sizes range from 1 (Cricetomys gambianus) to 10 (Saccostomus campestris).

Crocidura leucodon.text: Crocidura leucodon, and other central-European members of the genus, exhibit one of the more interesting parent/offspring behaviors of shrews: caravanning.

Crocodylus acutus.text: Not much information is known about particular mating habits between males and females, although they appear to follow some of the same mating habits (such as being polygynous) of the American crocodile (Crocodylus acutus).

Crocodylus moreletii.text: Studies among captive Crocodylus moreletii show females will respond to newborn vocalizations and open the nests.

Crocuta crocuta.text: Usually females will defend their young with great vigor, though there is a reported case of mothers standing idly by while a Crocuta crocuta killed and ate a juvenile. (Estes, 1991; Kingdon, 1979)

Crossarchus obscurus.text: In captivity, Crossarchus obscurus is known to live nine years (Goldman, 1987).

Crossaster papposus.text: Upon growing to 5cm in diameter, Crossaster papposus migrates to shallow water (4-8cm in diameter) and then, with increasing size, it gradually moves to greater depths.

Crotalus atrox.text: Crotalus atrox reaches sexual maturity at 3 years.

Crotalus molossus.text: There is not much available information about the lifespan and longevity of Crotalus molossus.

Crotalus viridis.text: In areas where females are scarce, males spend more time searching for females, and are not generally observed fighting over females. (Duvall, 1997; Fitch, 1998; Melli, 1999; Reptiles and Amphibians of North Dakota, 1999; Crotalus viridis viridis, 1999)

Crotaphytus collaris.text: Crotaphytus collaris courts and mates on the ground in spring to early summer.

Cryptomys damarensis.text: Cryptomys damarensis probably has a similar lifespan. (Nowak, 1999)

Cryptomys hottentotus.text: Lifespan and longevity is currently unknown for Damaraland mole-rats, although individuals of the closely related species, Cryptomys hottentotus, have lived nearly 10 years in captivity.

Cryptotis parva.text: Like all female mammals, Cryptotis parva females provide their newborns with milk until they are independent and can eat solid food.

Ctenocephalides felis.text: Optimal conditions for survival of Ctenocephalides felis are described by a temperature range of 26.7 to 31.5 degrees Celsius and a relative humidity between 50 and 92 percent.

Ctenodactylus gundi.text: The gestation period is unknown, but ranges from 69-79 days in Ctenodactylus gundi, a related species.

Ctenomys pearsoni.text: Ctenomys pearsoni exhibits highly motivated maternal behavior postpartum.

Ctenomys sociabilis.text: Ctenomys sociabilis is a seasonal breeder.

Ctenomys talarum.text: Young of Ctenomys talarum are reportedly able to fend for themselves by about 10 days of age, even though they are not the most precocious members of their genus at birth.

Cuculus canorus.text: Cuculus canorus is a brood parasite.

Culiseta melanura.text: Culiseta melanura have a unique life cycle for a mosquito; the mosquito over winters as a larva as opposed to an adult.

Cuora amboinensis.text: The longevity of Cuora amboinensis is usually from 25 to 30 years.

Cyanopsitta spixii.text: The 28-year lifespan of Cyanopsitta spixii is considerably shorter than other, larger macaws, but similar to its closest relative, Illiger's macaws which have a lifespan of approximately 30 years.

Cyclopterus lumpus.text: Lernaeocera branchialis develops into a copepodid, which attaches to an intermediate host, such as a lumpfish (e.g. Cyclopterus lumpus), sculpin (Cottidae), or flounder (Pleuronectidae).

Cyclura cornuta.text: This corresponds to the fact that Cyclura cornuta appears to be extremely territorial and males especially will attempt to dominate and intimidate conspecifics with head movements and body gyrations.

Cynodon dactylon.text: Eggs are placed on weedy grasses such as crabgrass Digiteria spp. and Bermuda grass Cynodon dactylon.

Cynogale bennettii.text: Very little information exists on the breeding patterns of Cynogale bennettii.

Cynopterus brachyotis.text: Cynopterus brachyotis lives about 20 to 30 years. (Crichton and Krutzsch, 2000)

Cynopterus sphinx.text: India, Cynopterus sphinx breeds twice per year.

Cyphotilapia frontosa.text: However, Cyphotilapia frontosa release their fry about twenty meters deep.

Cyprinodon diabolis.text: Cyprinodon diabolis uses the limestone bedrock as well as the algae that grows on it as a substrate for spawning.

D. albiventris.text: Although D. albiventris may live somewhat longer, it is not likely that they have a really long life.

D. albus.text: The breeding season occurs only once a year, so D. albus is monestrus.

D. arboreus.text: There is very limited information on parental investment in D. arboreus.

D. auratus.text: The mating season of D. auratus occurs throughout the entire rainy season of the rain forest, from mid-July through mid-September.

D. azureus.text: The lifespan of D. azureus is about 4-6 years in the wild.

D. compactus.text: Litter sizes of 1 to 6 young have been recorded, which is consistent with the average of 2 young per litter observed in D. compactus. (Nowak, 1999)

D. elator.text: It is likely that given the consistency of these parameters within the genus, D. elator is similar.

D. f. fuscus.text: In one study, brooding female D. f. fuscus returned to their nests after being displaced as much as 32 meters.

D. hybridus.text: The specific lifespan of D. hybridus is not known, but other species of armadillo have been reported to live anywhere from 9 to 40 years.

D. inustus.text: There is not much known about the mating systems of D. inustus but their relative in Australia, Dendrolagus lumholtzi, is known to be polygynous.

D. leporina.text: Though specific data on D. leporina longevity are unavailable, other members of the genus have lived 15 to 20 years in captivity.

D. marsupialis.text: Little information is available on specific lifespans of Didelphis aurita, but its close relative D. marsupialis has an average life span of 2 years in the wild. (Hagmann, 2003)

D. ordii.text: The average lifespan is 4.9 month, but this, is of course, misleading. Many kangaroo rats die young, and those who make it to adulthood can live a very long time. Although maximum lifespan for Dipodomys microps has not been reported, one captive D. ordii lived to be nearly 10 years old! (Hayssen, 1991; Nowak, 1999)

D. petechia.text: From its wintering grounds, D. petechia arrive in the northern areas with little time between migrations for the reproduction process, which at a minimum takes 45 days.

D. scottae.text: There is little information on longevity in D. scottae, however other Dendrolagus are known to live 20 years or more in captivity.

D. trivirgata.text: Limited research has been conducted on the breeding biology of D. trivirgata.

Dacelo novaeguineae.text: A captive laughing kookaburra (Dacelo novaeguineae) also lived over 15 years.

Dama dama.text: Dama dama usually give birth to one fawn after a gestation period of 33 to 35 weeks.

Damaliscus pygargus.text: Damaliscus pygargus can live up to 17 years. (Kingdom, 1997; Mills and Hes, 1997)

Danaus plexippes.text: They have also been observed chasing other insects while patrolling, including monarchs Danaus plexippes, black swallowtails Papilio polyxenes asterias, great spangled fritillaries Speyeria cybele and aphrodite fritillaries Speyeria aphrodite (B.J. Barton, personal observation, Kopper et al. 2001).

Danaus plexippus.text: The courtship of Danaus plexippus is fairly simple and less dependent on chemical pheromones in comparison with other species in its genus.

Daphnia.text: This stage of reproduction is most used for a rapid increase in Daphnia growth but requires more favorable conditions. The sexual stage of Daphnia reproduction occurs mainly in the winter during less favorable conditions caused by overcrowding, accumulation of wastes, lower food availability, and lower temperatures.

Daphnia pulex.text: Parthenogenesis occurs mainly in the summer, so that during summer an entire population of Daphnia pulex will consist almost completely of females.

Daptrius americanus.text: Two species of falconids, red-throated caracaras (Daptrius americanus) and collared falconets (Microhierax caerulescens) regularly breed cooperatively.

Dasyatis americana.text: Dasyatis americana is ovoviparous; the female carries eggs internally but does not nurture the fetuses.

Dasyprocta punctata.text: In Dasyprocta punctata and other Dasyprocta species, females usually raise one or two precocial young.

Dasyprocta ruatanica.text: The only lifespan information available for Dasyprocta ruatanica is that individuals have reached the age of 13.7 years in captivity. (Weigl and Jones, 2005)

Dasypus hybridus.text: Dasypus hybridus has between 4 and 12 young in each litter.

Dasypus novemcinctus.text: Nine banded armadillos (Dasypus novemcinctus) are weaned at 4 to 5 months and become mature sexually around 1 year. ("Armadillos", 2006; "Xenarthra; Family Dasypodidae", 1999)

Dasyurus geoffroii.text: Dasyurus geoffroii are independent at 18 weeks and weaned at 23 to 24 weeks, both the male and female are sexually mature at one year of age. (Collins 1973, Hyett et al 1980, Massicot 2000, Mawson 1996, Menkhorst et al 1995, Ride 1970)

Dasyurus hallucatus.text: The most successful reproduction of Dasyurus hallucatus occurs near creeklines due to the constant supply of water.

Dasyurus maculatus.text: Dasyurus maculatus has been kept alive in captivity for three to four years (Nowak, 1999).

Delphinapterus leucas.text: Lactation duration is unknown, but thought to be comparable to the white whale (Delphinapterus leucas) of 20 months.

Dendroaspis polylepis.text: Dendroaspis polylepis mate in the early spring.

Dendrobates auratus.text: For instance, the green poison dart frog, Dendrobates auratus, is polygynous. (Summers, 1990)

Dendrobates azureus.text: Dendrobates azureus usually breed in the months of February and March producing 5-10 offspring per clutch.

Dendrobates histrionicus.text: Dendrobates histrionicus is unique in how the tadpoles feed.

Dendrocopos leucotos.text: Dendrocopos leucotos begin mating in February.

Dendrogale murina.text: Dendrogale murina tend to breed when fruiting of local trees and shrubs is at its maximum (Blomstrom, 2001).

Dendrohyrax.text: One record of an anomolurid being held in captivity had the animal living in a cage for 14 months with a Dendrohyrax species.

Dendroica chrysoparia.text: During incubation Dendroica chrysoparia spends at least 75% of daylight hours on the nest.

Dendroicia virens.text: Adult survivorship amongst Dendroicia virens is high, with 67% yearly survival.

Dendrolagus.text: Living in tropical rainforest with little differentiation between seasons, Dendrolagus are not likely to be seasonal breeders, and, instead, are probably opportunistic breeders (Tyndale-Biscoe and Renfree, 1987).

Dendrolagus bennettianus.text: Also in the other tree kangaroo species of Australia, Dendrolagus bennettianus, males are very territorial with other males but their territory often overlaps with several females, leading to the idea that they are polygynous.

Dendrolagus lumholtzi.text: There is not much known about the mating systems of D. inustus but their relative in Australia, Dendrolagus lumholtzi, is known to be polygynous.

Dendrolagus matschiei.text: Whereas certain species of tree-kangaroo, such as Dendrolagus matschiei, have been successfully bred and studied in captivity, most are little studied so that reproductive behavior and processes are poorly understood.

Dendrolagus scottae.text: There is very little information on Dendrolagus scottae or other Dendrolagus species.

Dendromus melanotis.text: The gestation period for Dendromus melanotis is 23-27 days.

Dendromus mesomelas.text: However, a closely related species, Dendromus mesomelas, was documented in 1973 to live 3 years and 3 months in captivity.

Dermatemys mawii.text: This phenomenon helps Dermatemys mawii reproduce because it allows females to lay eggs in more secluded areas away from the normal river channel.

Dermatobia hominis.text: Mating in Dermatobia hominis begins with "pouncing" displays performed by a male in response to sexual readiness in a female, which is indicated by the protraction of the latter's abdomen or pseudovipositor.

Dermochelys coriacea.text: We have no information on the lifespan of Dermochelys coriacea. (Barbour and Ernst, 1972; Pope, 1939)

Desmodus rotundus.text: The relate common vampire bat (Desmodus rotundus) lives around 9 years in the wild. (Marlett, 2001)

Desmognathus ochrophaeus.text: Most Desmognathus ochrophaeus larvae have metamorphosed into the adult form after a few weeks, but a few go more quickly (probably nourished by especially large and rich yolk in their egg) or take much longer, up to 8 months (Bishop 1943; Hairston 1987, Virginia Fish and Wildlife Information Service 2002).

Diadema antillarum.text: The spawning of Diadema antillarum appears to be connected to the lunar calendar.

Diadophis punctatus.text: They originated from at least 50 racers, sharp-tailed snakes (Contia tenuis), ring-necked snakes (Diadophis punctatus), and gopher snakes (Pituophis catenifer) (Greene,1997). (Conant and Collins, 1998; Greene, 1997)

Diaemus youngi.text: The lifespan of Diaemus youngi has only been documented in captivity where they can live 20 years.

Diclidurus albus.text: Diclidurus albus is a rare animal to see, so its reproductive behaviors have yet to be studied in depth. (Ceballos and Medellin, 1988; Hernandez et al., 1985; Jones and Hood, 1993)

Didelphis albiventris.text: Didelphis albiventris reproduction is seasonal, but varies according to rainfall patterns.

Didelphis aurita.text: Little information is available on specific lifespans of Didelphis aurita, but its close relative D. marsupialis has an average life span of 2 years in the wild. (Hagmann, 2003)

Didelphis marsupialis.text: Using information from other South American Didelphidae like Didelphis marsupialis the females can have 2 to 3 litters per breeding season with an average of 7.3 young per litter. (Eisenberg and Redford, 1999; Gentile et al., 2000; Gentile, D'Andrea, and Cerqueira, 1995)

Digiteria spp..text: Eggs are placed on weedy grasses such as crabgrass Digiteria spp. and Bermuda grass Cynodon dactylon. (Opler, 1984)

Dinemellia dinemelli.text: African pygmy falcons rely on the social weavers (Philetairus socius) in the northeast part of their range and white-headed buffalo weavers (Dinemellia dinemelli) in the southwestern part of their range for nesting.

Diodon holocanthus.text: Until they are 10 days old, Diodon holocanthus larvae retain a thin shell covering, which is then lost (FLMNH).

Diphylla ecaudata.text: Diphylla ecaudata is sexually mature at 9 months and reproductively active throughout the year.

Dipodomys.text: There is an average of three litters per year for Dipodomys.

Dipodomys californicus.text: There isn't much data available on the specific reproductive behavior of Dipodomys californicus.

Dipodomys deserti.text: The mass of Dipodomys deserti at birth ranges between 2.2 and 4.6 g.

Dipodomys heermanni.text: Sexual maturity is achieved at some point past the third week; in congenerics of Dipodomys heermanni, maturity was achieved at times ranging from day 32 to day 56.

Dipodomys hermanni.text: In Dipodomys hermanni, hairs are reported to be visible at approximately 14 days of age.

Dipodomys merriami.text: Dipodomys merriami has a high reproductive rate.

Dipodomys microps.text: The average lifespan is 4.9 month, but this, is of course, misleading. Many kangaroo rats die young, and those who make it to adulthood can live a very long time. Although maximum lifespan for Dipodomys microps has not been reported, one captive D. ordii lived to be nearly 10 years old! (Hayssen, 1991; Nowak, 1999)

Dipodomys nitratoides.text: The time until weaning apparently varies, as Dipodomys nitratoides weans its young between 21 and 24 days, and Dipodomys panamintinus weans its young between 27 and 29 days.

Dipodomys ordii.text: The estrous cycle in Dipodomys ordii is short, lasting only 5-6 days.

Dipodomys panamintinus.text: The time until weaning apparently varies, as Dipodomys nitratoides weans its young between 21 and 24 days, and Dipodomys panamintinus weans its young between 27 and 29 days.

Dipodomys venustus.text: Female Dipodomys venustus have one to two litters per year with two to four young per litter.

Dipus sagitta.text: Dipus sagitta breeds in the same season as P. ctenodactylus and appears to have other similarities as well.

Dipylidium caninum.text: When Dipylidium caninum finally reaches its definitive host it can reach sexual maturity.

Dorcopsis luctuosa.text: Female Dorcopsis luctuosa reach maturity at 15 months.

Dorcopsis muelleri.text: In a closely related species, Dorcopsis muelleri, the time until weaning is 270 days.

Dorcopsulus luctuosa.text: However, a related species found in the same geographic range but at lower altitudes, Dorcopsulus luctuosa, has a maximum lifespan of eight years.

Dorcopsulus macleayi.text: Dorcopsulus macleayi probably has similar longevity. (Fisher, Owens, and Johnson, 2001)

Dorosoma cepedianum.text: The Dorosoma cepedianum incubation period is two to four days, depending on the water temperature and environmental conditions.

Dosidicus gigas.text: Dosidicus gigas only has one reproductive cycle during their lifetime, so they are known as monocyclic.

Dracaena fragrans.text: Nests are typically placed 0.3 to 2 meters above ground, often in Dracaena fragrans axils or at the base of a branch.

Dracunculus insignis.text: The rare occurrence of Dracunculus insignis males is due to their death directly following mating. (Barnes, 1987; Brusca and Brusca, 2003; Crichton and Beverly-Burton, 1975; Panciera and Stockham, 1988; Roberts, Janovy, and Jr., 2000)

Dromaius novaehollandiae.text: If mud is not available, the birds may use animal dung, including that of Dromaius novaehollandiae.

Dromiciops gliroides.text: Dromiciops gliroides breeds in the spring and has one litter of 1-4 young per year.

Drosophila melanogaster.text: As in all insect species Drosophila melanogaster lays eggs.

Dryocopus pileatus.text: Nest sites are usually in dark places such as caves or hollow trees (Vaux’s swifts (Chaetura vauxi) will nest in the cavities made by pileated woodpeckers (Dryocopus pileatus)).

Dryomys nitedula.text: Lifespans of four years have been reported for other wild dormice (Dryomys nitedula and Muscardinus avellanarius).

Muscardinus avellanarius.text: Muscardinus avellanarius has 1 or 2 litters per year.

Dumetella carolinensis.text: Turdus americanus, Dumetella carolinensis and Hylocichla mustelina.

E. alpestris.text: Breeding often occurs very early in the spring, but most E. alpestris begin breeding in June.

E. blennioides.text: Darters such as E. blennioides are also extremely sensitive to siltation and turbidity.

E. coqui.text: The bananaquit (Coereba flaveola portoricensis), Puerto Rican bullfinch (Loxigilla portoricensis) and Puerto Rican tody (Todus mexicanus) are all birds which share nests with E. coqui.

E. forficatus.text: There is no specific information available on the lifespan of E. forficatus, but the lifespan of one Elanus leucurus was recorded to be nearly 6 years.

E. fulvus.text: It is likely that E. fulvus is similar.

E. granti.text: One source suggests that the young of E. granti are evicted from mother's area when they weigh approximately 35 to 45 g.

E. horridus.text: The lifespan of E. horridus is not known.

E. major.text: There is no information about reproductive behavior in E. major but there is some information on its closest relative, E. spelaea.

E. onager.text: The maximum lifespan of E. onager is reported to be approximately 40 years.

E. rozeti.text: The longest known lifespan of a E. rozeti was about 7 years, though the age of the animal was not scientifically determined.

E. ruber.text: Young E. ruber are altricial, when they first hatch, they are helpless and cannot even hold up their heads.

E. semivillosus.text: Average number of offspring for E. semivillosus is 2. (Nowak, 2004; Woods, 1982)

E. spelaea.text: There is no information about reproductive behavior in E. major but there is some information on its closest relative, E. spelaea.

E. triquetra.text: Michigan, reproduction of E. triquetra probably occurs from mid-July to August when water temperatures are from 21 to 27 degrees C.

E. vancoveri.text: Many individuals have been found with characteristics of both Eudistylia polymorpha and E. vancoveri, implying that hybridization between the two species may occur. (Fox 1994; Strathmann, 1987)

E. zebra.text: Most E. zebra foals leave their maternal herds in summer.

Echeneis naucrates.text: When the newly-hatched Echeneis naucrates are still developing, the sucking device begins forming.

Echimys semivillosus.text: Female Echimys semivillosus birth their young in arboreal dens.

Echinococcus multilocularis.text: Epidemiology, clinical findings and treatment]Infection with the fox dwarf tapeworm, Echinococcus multilocularis, has for the first time been found in a fox in Denmark, and E. multilocularis infection is therefore now a possible diagnosis in Danish patients.

Echinophthirius horridus.text: Echinophthirius horridus reproduces only when its seal hosts are on land (Thompson, 1998).

Echymipera kalubu.text: The gestation period for Echymipera kalubu is 120 days and frequently, one to three young are found in the female's pouch. Anderson, et al.

Egretta thula.text: Snowy egrets generally live between 2 and 17 years. Egretta thula has been subject to nematode parasitism, which causes death.

Egretta tricolor.text: The female Egretta tricolor lays, on average, 3-4 bluish colored eggs once a year.

Eidolon helvum.text: The highest lifespans in captivity of other Pteropodidae species include: straw-colored fruit bats (Eidolon helvum), 21.8 years; flying foxes (Pteropus), 31.4 years; and rousette fruit bats (Rousettus), 22.9 years. (Jones, 1982)

Eira barbara.text: Some believe that the estrous cycle of Eira barbara is seasonal, with births occuring in March and July.

Elanus leucurus.text: There is no specific information available on the lifespan of E. forficatus, but the lifespan of one Elanus leucurus was recorded to be nearly 6 years. (Clapp, Klimkiewicz, and Kennard, 1982; National Audubon Society, 2001)

Elephantulus.text: The lifespan of the Rock Elephant Shrew is not generally well known though the general lifespan of some Elephantulus species is thought to be near 4 to 6 years in the wild and 1.5 to 3 years in captivity (Rathbun & Fons 1990).

Elephantulus rozeti.text: Elephantulus rozeti individuals breed seasonally, usually from January to August, depending on their environment.

Elephantulus rufescens.text: However, mating behavior of Elephantulus rufescens was observed in the lab.

Eleutherodactylus coqui.text: Eleutherodactylus coqui reproduce year round, but reproduction rates increase during the rainy season.

Eliomys quercinus.text: Young Eliomys quercinus are born in a nest which is larger than the sleeping nests typical of this species.

Elliptio dilatata.text: Michigan, Elliptio dilatata was gravid from mid-May to early August.

Empidonax flaviventris.text: Empidonax flaviventris nests on or near the ground.

Empidonax hammondii.text: Empidonax hammondii females have 3-4 whitish or yellowish eggs and incubate the eggs for 12-15 days.

Emydoidea blandingii.text: In this species, the sex of the hatchling is independent of incubation temperature, a departure from the trend in closely related emydid species (such as Clemmys guttata and Emydoidea blandingii) in which embryonic sex differentiation is directly related to nest temperatures during the middle third of the incubation period (Ewert and Nelson, 1991).

Emys orbicularis.text: Records have shown average Emys orbicularis turtles living fifteen years or longer and adults may potentially live for decades.

Enoplosus armatus.text: The reproduction of Enoplosus armatus has not been well studied.

Ensis directus.text: There are separate male and female sexes in Ensis directus.

Enterobius vermicularis.text: The life cycle of Enterobius vermicularis is about two months long. Enterobius vermicularis is common among children because thumb-sucking is common at this age.

Eonycteris major.text: There is little available information on mating systems in Eonycteris major.

Epioblasma torulosa.text: Other Epioblasma species have recently been observed trapping fish hosts within their valves, and Epioblasma torulosa may do the same. (Barnhart and Roston, 2005; Environment Canada, 2004b; Lefevre and Curtis, 1912; Watters, 1995)

Epomorphorus gambianus.text: Epomorphorus gambianus breeds twice annually, with births occurring during the rainy seasons.
