Eptesicus fuscus.text: Eptesicus fuscus employs delayed fertilization as a reproductive strategy.

Equus hemionus.text: Nowak (1999) reports that lactation in female Equus hemionus (a species of wild ass in which some authorities include onagers) nurse their young for between 1 and 1.5 years.

Equus kiang.text: Male Equus kiang mob females and guard them from rival males.

Equus zebra zebra.text: Equus zebra zebra young leave their maternal herds of their own volition.

Eremitalpa granti.text: Eremitalpa granti is believed to give birth to one to two naked, virtually helpless young.

Eremophila alpestris.text: The longest living known individuals are an 8 year, 5 month old skylark (Alauda arvensis) and a 7 year 11 month old horned lark (Eremophila alpestris).

Erinaceus europaeus.text: Of the insectivores, only the African hedgehog (Atelerix albiventris) and the European hedgehog (Erinaceus europaeus) are commonly kept as pets and, consequently, the insectivore section concentrates on discussing these two species.

Erpetoichthys calabaricus.text: Erpetoichthys calabaricus has external fertilization of eggs with sperm.

Esox americanus.text: Esox americanus is one of the earliest spawning fishes in the spring.

Esox lucius.text: With their insatiable eating habits young Esox lucius grow rapidly in both length and weight.

Estheostma blennioides.text: The breeding season of Estheostma blennioides is from April to June; spawning activity peaks in May.

Etheostoma blennioides.text: The only additional parental investment observed in Etheostoma blennioides is the guarding of fertilized eggs by the male parent (Radabaugh, 1989).

Etheostoma nigrum.text: However in the closely related Johnny darters, Etheostoma nigrum, suggested lifespan is 3 years. ("Kentucky AWAKE", 2005; "Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources", 2003)

Eubalaena australis.text: However, it is likely that mating is similar to other right whale species: Eubalaena australis and Eubalaena glacialis.

Eubalaena glacialis.text: Sometimes, as with northern right whales (Eubalaena glacialis), courtship behavior can be observed at the surface.

Eubalaena japonica.text: Mating systems have not been described for Eubalaena japonica.

Eudistylia polymorpha.text: Many individuals have been found with characteristics of both Eudistylia polymorpha and E. vancoveri, implying that hybridization between the two species may occur. (Fox 1994; Strathmann, 1987)

Eudocimus Albus.text: Eudocimus Albus usually lives for about 16 years in the wild and 20 years in captivity; the oldest known captive individual lived 31 years. (Hancock, Kushlan, and Kahl, 1992; Hill, 2001; Ricklefs, 2000)

Eudocimus albus.text: Eudocimus albus usually lives for about 16 years in the wild and 20 years in captivity; the oldest known captive individual lived 31 years. (Hancock, Kushlan, and Kahl, 1992; Hill, 2001; Ricklefs, 2000)

Eudocimus ruber.text: Eudocimus ruber has a colonial and social breeding system.

Eudyptes robustus.text: There are around 135 breeding colonies for Eudyptes robustus on Snares Island, with approximately two nests per square meter.

Eudyptes schlegeli.text: Eudyptes schlegeli are known to breed in both large and small colonies.

Eudyptes sclateri.text: Eudyptes sclateri pairs breed in large colonies usually with rockhopper penguins (Eudyptes chrysocome).

Eudyptes chrysocome.text: Eudyptes sclateri pairs breed in large colonies usually with rockhopper penguins (Eudyptes chrysocome).

Eudyptula minor.text: The breeding season for Eudyptula minor is between August and December, with peak egg laying in August and November.

Eulemur coronatus.text: Eulemur coronatus is probably like other members in the genus in regard to lifespan.

Eulemur fulvus.text: However, another member of the genus, Eulemur fulvus is known to have reached an age of 36 years in captivity.

Eulemur macaco.text: An individual which was a hybrid of E. fulvus and Eulemur macaco lived for 39 years in captivity.

Eulipoa wallacei.text: Species that use clumped geothermal incubation sites may aggregate in large numbers (over 50,000) onto communal incubation sites. Megapodius spp., Eulipoa wallacei, and perhaps Talegalla are thought to exhibit female-defense monogamy.

Eumops.text: Eumops genus, Eumops dabbenei males have a throat sac that swells with a phermone-laden musk during the breeding season.

Eumops dabbenei.text: Like some other members of the Eumops genus, Eumops dabbenei males have a throat sac that swells with a phermone-laden musk during the breeding season.

Eumops genus.text: Like some other members of the Eumops genus, Eumops dabbenei males have a throat sac that swells with a phermone-laden musk during the breeding season.

Eumops perotis.text: Eumops perotis is a eutherian with a gestation period of approximately 80 to 90 days.

Euoticus elegantulus.text: Euoticus elegantulus has no fixed breeding season.

Eupetaurus cinereus.text: Very little is actually known about the reproduction of Eupetaurus cinereus.

Euphonia luteicapilla.text: Euphonia luteicapilla builds covered nests with a side entrance.

Euphydryas editha.text: Euphydryas editha are protandrous - males typically emerge four to eight days prior to the emergence of females.

Euplectella aspergillum.text: Some sponges have two sexes, and individuals have only one sex, but it is likely that Euplectella aspergillum is hermaphroditic, producing both male and female gametes at different times.

Eupodotis senegalensis.text: Courtship feeding in white-bellied bustards (Eupodotis senegalensis) suggests monogamous pairing in some bustards, but this has not been reported in Kori bustards. The breeding season is different in the two subspecies of Kori bustards.

Eurycea nana.text: There is only vague information on the reproduction of Eurycea nana and eggs have never been found in nature.

Eurycea rathbuni.text: Little is known about the reproduction of Eurycea rathbuni.

Eurycea sosorum.text: Not many details of the reproduction of Eurycea sosorum are known.

Eurytides marcellus.text: An adult Eurytides marcellus butterfly can live up to 6 months in its natural environment. (Holland, 1910; Parenti, 1972; Tveten and Tveten, 1996)

F. s. silvestris.text: European wild cats (F. s. silvestris) breeding occurs in late winter (January to March) and births occur in the spring, usually in May.

F. tunnunculus.text: There is little data on the lifespan of F. tunnunculus in the wild.

Falco biarmicus.text: We do not have information on the lifespan of Falco biarmicus at this time.

Falco columbarius.text: This aggressive behavior towards other predatory birds is beneficial to other woodland song and ground birds in the nesting range; since Falco columbarius hunts only in open country, thereby leaving the woodland birds relatively free from predators during the mating season.

Falco columbarius bendirei.text: Falco columbarius bendirei: Breeds in northwestern Alaska to northern Saskatchewan and into northern California.

Falco columbarius columbarius.text: Falco columbarius columbarius: Breeds in eastern Canada to the eastern border of the Great Plains and southwards into Nova Scotia and northern Michigan.

Falco columbarius richardsoni.text: Falco columbarius richardsoni: Breeding range is located in the Great Plains from southern Alberta and Saskatchewan to northern Montana and North Dakota.

Falco columbarius suckleyi.text: Falco columbarius suckleyi: Breeding occurs only in western British Columbia and perhaps on Vancouver Island.

Falco eleonorae.text: There is no information available on lifespan in Falco eleonorae.

Falco mexicanus.text: One calculation predicted Falco mexicanus longevity to be 15.6 years.

Falco peregrinus.text: The mating system is similar to that of peregrine falcons (Falco peregrinus) and gryfalcons (Falco rusticolus).

Falco rusticolus.text: The mating system is similar to that of peregrine falcons (Falco peregrinus) and gryfalcons (Falco rusticolus).

Falcon biarmicus.text: Falco biarmicus is monogamous; both males and females engage in elaborate flying and loud crying as part of the courtship display. The breeding season for Falcon biarmicus varies significantly throughout its range.

Farancia erythrogramma.text: Very little is known about the courtship and mating behavior of Farancia erythrogramma.

Felis chaus.text: Felis chaus has a polyestrous reproductive cycle.

Feresa attenuata.text: Nothing is known of the birthing habits of melon-headed whales (their close relatives, Feresa attenuata, generally have only 1 calf).

Fossa fossana.text: Fossa fossana form pairs around the time of mating, and each pair may have a home range of about a square mile during the mating season.

Fratercula cirrhata.text: Fratercula cirrhata usually begin breeding in April, although mating activity has been seen as early as March and as late as May in some cases.

Fratercula coniculata.text: When Fratercula coniculata has reached this stage, they return to land in the summer to breed.

Fundulus heteroclitus.text: In the present study, a variety of techniques were used to characterize this toxin defense system in killifish (Fundulus heteroclitus) hepatocytes.

Furcifer lateralis.text: Furcifer lateralis matures in a very short period of time, and are generally able to reproduce by three months of age.

Fusconaia flava.text: Fusconaia flava is a short-term brooder.

G. alleni.text: In captivity G. alleni has been found to live about 12 years.

G. arenarius.text: The gestation period of G. arenarius is 18 to 19 days and females have 3 to 4 offspring per reproductive effort.

G. aurita.text: However, because G. aurita is a mammal, we know that females provide extensive maternal care.

G. bengalensis.text: The breeding season of G. bengalensis is from October to March.

G. brownii.text: Little is known about the mating system of prehensile-tailed hutias, but two species in the same family, Geocapromys ingrahami and G. brownii, breed year round.

G. californianus.text: The lifespan of G. californianus is 7 to 8 years.

G. capensis.text: Information on the mating system of G. capensis is not available.

G. comissarisi.text: G. comissarisi is unknown, but an individual of a related species, G. soricina lived to 10 years in captivity.

G. cuja.text: Gestation in G. cuja is complete after about 40 days, when 2 to 4 offspring are produced.

G. dorcas.text: Depending on local climate, a group of G. dorcas will consist of one or two males with a harem of females or just a male-female pair.

G. fasciata.text: Nothing is known about parental investment of G. fasciata.

G. grandidieri.text: No specific studies have been conducted on the development of G. grandidieri, but it seems that it is similar to that of other members of the mongoose family.

G. granti.text: The mother-fawn relationship is the only persistent relationship in G. granti.

G. ingrahami.text: There is no available information on the lifespan of M. prehensilis, but G. ingrahami can reach the age of 6 years in the wild. (Clough, 1974)

G. piscivora.text: There is currently no available information about the lifespan of G. piscivora.

G. pseudogeographica konii.text: A male G. pseudogeographica konii that was caught as a juvenile, lived for 35 years and 5 months at the Columbus Zoo.

G. soricina.text: G. comissarisi is unknown, but an individual of a related species, G. soricina lived to 10 years in captivity.

G. venusta.text: No information on reproduction is available for G. venusta.

G. vittata.text: Greater grisons (G. vittata) have lived more than 10 years in captivity.

G. zanzibaricus.text: The longest lifespan of a captive G. zanzibaricus is 12.2 years. ("An Age entry for Galagoides zanzibaricus", 2005)

Gabon bushbabies.text: Although gestation length could not be found in the primary literature for Gabon bushbabies, gestation length in other Galago species can range from 111 days to 142 days (Charles-Dominique, 1977a), with smaller species exhibiting shorter gestational lengths.

Galago alleni.text: Other aspects of their reproduction may be similar to their close relative, Galago alleni.

Galago demidoff.text: Information on the gestation period and the number of offspring born are not available for Galago thomasi, however, in Galago demidoff females have a gestation period of 111 to 114 days and one young at a time.

Galago senegalensis.text: Another member of the genus, Galago senegalensis, is reported to have reached a maximum age of nearly 19 years in captivity.

Galago thomasi.text: Information on the gestation period and the number of offspring born are not available for Galago thomasi, however, in Galago demidoff females have a gestation period of 111 to 114 days and one young at a time.

Galerella sanguinea.text: In Galerella sanguinea, the male takes no part in the raising of the young.

Galidia elegans.text: Galidia elegans breed seasonally, from April until November.

Galidictis fasciata.text: Galidictis fasciata is probably similar to the other Malagasy herpestids in these characteristics, but more research is needed to know for sure. (Nowak, 1999)

Gallicolumba luzonica.text: Gallicolumba luzonica has a very long lifespan, usually living 15 years in the wild.

Gammarus fasciatus.text: Unlike other Crustacea, the young Gammarus fasciatus do not undergo metamorphosis. (Larousse Encyclopedia of the Animal World 1975; Meglitsch 1991; Pearse 1987; McMaster University)

Gasteropelecus sternicla.text: Research has shown that Gasteropelecus sternicla only breed for a short period coinciding with the start of the rainy season.

Gavialis gangeticus.text: The only record of longevity in Gavialis gangeticus is of a captive individual at the London Zoo, where one was estimated at 29 years old.

Gazella dorcas.text: In captivity Gazella dorcas can live up to 15 years.

Gehyra vorax.text: Like some other members of the family Gekkonidae, Gehyra vorax uses vocalizations when trying to find a mate or marking its territory.

Genetta genetta.text: Presumed to be similar to Genetta genetta with the range of single male overlapping that of several females, and from 1-2 reproductive cycles per year depending upon latitude.

Genetta tigrina.text: Very little is known about the reproductive patterns in Genetta tigrina.

Geocapromys brownii.text: Geocapromys brownii produces 1 to 3 young after a 123 day gestation period; the young can eat solid foods roughly 30 hours after birth.

Geocapromys ingrahami.text: Little is known about the mating system of prehensile-tailed hutias, but two species in the same family, Geocapromys ingrahami and G. brownii, breed year round.

Georychus capensis.text: Georychus capensis may live as long as 3 years in the wild. (Nowak, 1999)

Gerbillurus setzeri.text: Information about the postnatal development of Gerbillurus setzeri has been difficult to observe primarily because they are difficult to breed in captivity.

Giraffa camelopardalis.text: Most notable in this regard are Artiodactyla such as Connochaetes or Giraffa camelopardalis.

Glaucidium californicum.text: Glaucidium californicum have clutch sizes that range from 3 to 7, which the female incubates for about 29 days while the male is responsible for bringing back food to the nest.

Glironia venusta.text: No studies have been published about the lifespan of Glironia venusta.

Glis glis.text: Wild edible dormice (Glis glis) have been reported to live up to 12 years.

Glossophaga soricina.text: Reproductive behavior varies somewhat geographically, though most accounts indicate that Glossophaga soricina either breeds continuously throughout the year or is bimodally polyestrous.

Glyptemys insculpta.text: While mounted, the male may thump the female's shell with his plastron, a behavior common in related wood turtles (Glyptemys insculpta).

Gobiosoma oceanops.text: However, there is evidence that some gobies recognize mates as individuals (Gobiosoma oceanops), possibly through olfactory cues.

Gorgonia ventalina.text: There are several potential causes of death for Gorgonia ventalina.

Graphiurus murinus.text: Eliomys quercinus and Graphiurus murinus each live 5 to 6 years in captivity (Carey and Judge 2002). (Carey and Judge, 2002; Ruf et al., 2006)

Graptemys.text: Generally, species within the Graptemys genus produce mostly males at temperatures lower than 28 degrees Celsius and mostly females at temperatures 30 degrees Celsius or above, although specific temperatures for Graptemys versa have not been found.

Graptemys flavimaculata.text: It is believed that Graptemys flavimaculata have a similar reproductive pattern to other related Graptemys species which reach reproductive maturity between the ages of 6 to 9 years.

Graptemys versa.text: Generally, species within the Graptemys genus produce mostly males at temperatures lower than 28 degrees Celsius and mostly females at temperatures 30 degrees Celsius or above, although specific temperatures for Graptemys versa have not been found.

Graptemys pseudogeographica.text: Graptemys pseudogeographica mate twice a year in April and again in October and November.

Grus japonensis.text: Grus japonensis breeds in the spring and summer.

Grus leucogeranus.text: The lifespan of Grus leucogeranus in the wild is unknown at this time, but predicted longevity is shorter than highest lifespans reached in captivity. (Friedman, 1992)

Gymnobelideus leadbeateri.text: Similar to most marsupials in Australia, Gymnobelideus leadbeateri has a very short gestation period.

Gymnogyps californianus.text: Young Gymnogyps californianus remain with the parents for up to a year before leaving the nest; the young begin to fly at 6 to 7 months. (Greenway 1967; Mountfort 1988)

Gymnothorax funebris.text: The reproductive habits of Gymnothorax funebris are not well known.

Gymnothorax mordax.text: Gymnothorax mordax reproduces by external fertilization.

Gyps bengalensis.text: There is little available information on the lifespan of Gyps bengalensis.

H. aureus.text: The following data on reproduction come from another member of the same genus, Hapalemur griseus, to which H. aureus may bear some similarity. Hapalemur griseus gives birth to one or two young in October to February.

H. chrysoscelis.text: Unfotunately, it was not distinguished as H. chrysoscelis or H. versicolor. The potential lifespan in captivity and the wild is unknown. (Harding, 1997)

H. commersoni.text: Females may carry their young with them for about the first month of its life, as in Hipposideros fulvus, although data on H. commersoni are lacking on this facet of behavior.

H. concolor.text: It is likely that H. concolor is similar.

H. gabriellae.text: The only data on the lifespan of H. gabriellae is from captivity, where individuals of this species can live up to 50 years.

H. griseus.text: The pups of H. griseus, however, are speculated to mature around 11 to 14 years for males and 18 to 35 years for females.

H. gymnurus.text: Additional information on reproductive behavior for H. gymnurus is not available, but time of weaning is three to four weeks, and sexual maturity is reached at five months in the closely related species Proechimys semispinosus.

H. hoolock.text: Like all gibbon species, H. hoolock is monogamous (Nowak, 1999).

H. klossii.text: The gestation period of H. klossii lasts 7 to 8 months, with one infant born every 2 to 3 years.

H. kuda.text: The natural lifespan of H. kuda and its relatives are virtually unknown ("Project Seahorse", 2003).

H. lar.text: It is likely that H. lar is like other members of the genus in terms of its lifespan.

H. lepidus.text: Though little specific information is available on Hylopetes fimbriatus, a close relative, H. lepidus, exhibits no specific reproduction time.

H. liberiensis.text: Very little is known about the reproductive behavior of H. liberiensis in the wild.

H. nigriceps.text: The average litter size is 6.3 for lowland streaked tenrecs (H. semispinosus) and 1.3 for highland streaked tenrecs (H. nigriceps).

H. rubicundus.text: Unlike other members of the family however, the male H. rubicundus spends an inordinate amount of time and energy (approximately an entire month) cleaning and preparing an inviting algal mat more than an inch thick and as large as a tire in circumference.

H. semispinosus.text: The average litter size is 6.3 for lowland streaked tenrecs (H. semispinosus) and 1.3 for highland streaked tenrecs (H. nigriceps).

H. underwoodi.text: The lifespan of H. underwoodi is unknown.

H. versicolor.text: Unfotunately, it was not distinguished as H. chrysoscelis or H. versicolor. The potential lifespan in captivity and the wild is unknown. (Harding, 1997)

H. yaguarondi.text: It is not known what the lifespan of H. yaguarondi is in the wild.

H. zosterae.text: Smaller species of seahorses like H. zosterae reach maturity within about 4 months.

Haematobia irritans.text: In colder climates, however, the life cycle of Haematobia irritans may take up to three weeks for completion. (Skidmore, 1985)

Haematoloechus medioplexus.text: Haematoloechus medioplexus go through a complex life cycle that involves seven developmental stages: the egg, the miracidium, the sporocyst, the redia, the cercaria, the metacercaria, and the adult.

Haematopinus suis.text: Haematopinus suis is a permanent parasite; it spends its entire life cycle on the swine host.

Halaelurus lineatus.text: In this case several eggs develop in each oviduct, and hatching time tends to be shorter (23 to 36 days in Halaelurus lineatus).

Halcyon smyrnensis.text: Halcyon smyrnensis breeds seasonally and in monogamous pairs.

Haliaeetus albicilla.text: Steller's sea eagles, but it is thought to be similar to that of their close relatives, white-tailed sea eagles (Haliaeetus albicilla), which live 20 to 25 years in the wild.

Halichoerus grypus.text: In general, pinniped carnivores live longer than fissiped carnivores, with several species (odobenus rosmarus, Halichoerus grypus, Phoca hispida, Phoca caspica, and Phoca sibirica) reported to live 40 or more years in the wild. (Carey and Judge, 2002; King, 1989)

Haliclystus auricula.text: Haliclystus auricula is unusual in that it is a Schyphozoan, but it lives in the polyp stage.

Hapalemur aureus.text: Hapalemur aureus is probably similarly long-lived.

Hapalemur griseus.text: The following data on reproduction come from another member of the same genus, Hapalemur griseus, to which H. aureus may bear some similarity. Hapalemur griseus gives birth to one or two young in October to February.

Haplonycteris fischeri.text: This makes Haplonycteris fischeri the bat species with the longest known gestation period (Heidemann, 1989).

Haplophryne mollis.text: After finding their mate, males attach themselves to females with hooked denticles, and in some species (Haplophryne mollis) the tissue between the two fuses; the males become permanently attached and receive nourishment from the female while the testes develop. (Bertelson and Pietsch, 1998)

Helarctos malayanus.text: Births in Helarctos malayanus may occur at any time of the year.

Helix pomatia.text: Mating in Helix pomatia usually takes place among mature snails in the late spring and early summer, but can occur as last as October.

Heloderma suspectum.text: Females may guard their eggs for some time after laying, fending off predatory Gila monsters (Heloderma suspectum) and curious humans.

Helostoma temmincki.text: Helostoma temmincki are oviparous and dioecious and demonstrate external fertilization.

Hemibelideus lemuroides.text: Young Hemibelideus lemuroides are altricial, unable to provide for themselves.

Hemicentetes semispinosus.text: Lowland streaked tenrecs (Hemicentetes semispinosus) live as long as 30 months in captivity and highland streaked tenrecs (H. nigriceps) up to 3 years. How long either species lives in the wild is unknown. (Stephenson, 2007)

Hemidactylium scutatum.text: It takes between two and three years for Hemidactylium scutatum to reach sexual maturity.

Hemiechinus aethiopicus.text: Deaf and blind, a young Hemiechinus aethiopicus is born fairly helpless.

Hemiechinus auritus.text: Studies of desert hedgehogs, including P. micropus, often do not specify the species, particularly in work involving both P. micropus and long-eared hedgehogs (Hemiechinus auritus), which are also native to the region.

Hemiechinus micropus.text: Hemiechinus micropus will breed once per year, generally in the spring or summer between April and September.

Hemigalus derbyanus.text: Viverridae, of which Hemigalus derbyanus is a member, there are generally two litters per year, one in the spring and one in the fall.

Hemiphractus.text: July, an Hemiphractus johnsoni was found with seventeen eggs in her dorsal pouch.

Hemiphractus johnsoni.text: In the month of July, an Hemiphractus johnsoni was found with seventeen eggs in her dorsal pouch.

Hemiprocne comata.text: Crested treeswift (Hemiprocne coronata) eggs are 23 to 26 by 15.5 to 19 mm, grey-rumped treeswift (Hemiprocne longipennis) eggs are 23 to 24.5 by 17 to 18 mm, whiskered treeswift (Hemiprocne comata) eggs are 12 by 15 mm and moustached treeswift (Hemiprocne mystacea) eggs are 30 by 20mm.

Hemiprocne coronata.text: Crested treeswift (Hemiprocne coronata) eggs are 23 to 26 by 15.5 to 19 mm, grey-rumped treeswift (Hemiprocne longipennis) eggs are 23 to 24.5 by 17 to 18 mm, whiskered treeswift (Hemiprocne comata) eggs are 12 by 15 mm and moustached treeswift (Hemiprocne mystacea) eggs are 30 by 20mm.

Hemiprocne longipennis.text: Crested treeswift (Hemiprocne coronata) eggs are 23 to 26 by 15.5 to 19 mm, grey-rumped treeswift (Hemiprocne longipennis) eggs are 23 to 24.5 by 17 to 18 mm, whiskered treeswift (Hemiprocne comata) eggs are 12 by 15 mm and moustached treeswift (Hemiprocne mystacea) eggs are 30 by 20mm.

Hemiprocne mystacea.text: Crested treeswift (Hemiprocne coronata) eggs are 23 to 26 by 15.5 to 19 mm, grey-rumped treeswift (Hemiprocne longipennis) eggs are 23 to 24.5 by 17 to 18 mm, whiskered treeswift (Hemiprocne comata) eggs are 12 by 15 mm and moustached treeswift (Hemiprocne mystacea) eggs are 30 by 20mm.

Hemitragus hylocrius.text: It is interesting that Hemitragus jemlahicus and Hemitragus hylocrius are polygamous and Hemitragus jayakari is only polygamous in captivity.

Hemitragus jayakari.text: It is interesting that Hemitragus jemlahicus and Hemitragus hylocrius are polygamous and Hemitragus jayakari is only polygamous in captivity.

Hemitragus jemlahicus.text: Only rarely does the competitive display lead to direct head-to-head wrestling, which in Hemitragus jemlahicus has been described as "half-hearted" relative to other horned or antlered mammals. (Forsyth 1998, Forsyth and Hickling 1998, Huffman; Pare, Barrette, and Prescott 1996, Tustin 1990)

Henricia sanguinolenta.text: The larvae of Henricia sanguinolenta do not go through the free-swimming larval stage as most sea star larvae do.

Hepsetus odoe.text: The onset of the spawning season varies depending upon the region, but the method is consistant across Hepsetus odoe populations.

Hermissenda crassicornis.text: The Hermissenda crassicornis can lay a wide range of eggs on a strand, containing from a few to a million.

Herpestes edwardsii.text: Herpestes edwardsii reproduces rapidly, with females giving birth to two or three litters per year.

Heterocephalus glaber.text: Heterocephalus glaber have a unique mating system among mammals.

Heterodon nasicus.text: The mating season for Heterodon nasicus occurs between the months of June and August, as males actively seek out females to breed with.

Heteromys desmarestianus.text: Heteromys desmarestianus breeds year-round, but during extended dry periods some males and females may become reproductively inactive.

Hexanchus griseus.text: There is not much information pertaining to the reproductive behavior of Hexanchus griseus; however, there is some hypothetical information available.

Hexaprotodon liberiensis.text: The lifespan of Hexaprotodon liberiensis individuals in the wild is unknown.

Hippocampus erectus.text: With Hippocampus erectus, as with all seahorses, it is the male that cares for the young.

Hippocampus zosterae.text: Hippocampus zosterae, being a smaller species, is expected to live on average one year in the wild and in captivity (if given proper care) (Lourie et al., 2004).

Hipposideros commersoni.text: Hipposideros commersoni males exhibit a form of resource defense polygyny, protecting access to areas of daylight roosts.

Hipposideros fulvus.text: Mating occurs among Hipposideros fulvus every year in mid-November.

Hipposideros galeritus.text: Examples include Vampyrum spectrum, Lavia frons, Hipposideros galeritus, H. beatus, Nycteris hispida, N. arge, N. nana, and some Kerivoula species.

Hippotragus niger.text: Hippotragus niger females usually undergo only one estrous cycle per breeding season that last from May to July, with a peak mating in June.

Hirudo medicinalis.text: Hirudo medicinalis breeds once during an annual season that spans June through August.

Hirundo rustica.text: Male and female bank swallows share in incubating young, which allows them to lay eggs earlier in the season, when the weather is colder, than other swallow species (Hirundinidae) in which females only incubate eggs (such as Hirundo rustica).

Homo sapiens.text: As in Homo sapiens, there is no fixed breeding season for gorillas, and females menstruate every 28 days.

Hoplomys gymnurus.text: Little is known about the lifespan of Hoplomys gymnurus.

Hydrodamalis.text: Few details are known of the mating system of Hydrodamalis.

Hyla regilla.text: Young Hyla regilla are sexually mature at about one year of age (Krahling, 2000).

Hylobates leucogenys.text: The average lifespan of Hylobates leucogenys in the wild is twenty-eight years. (Cawthon Lang, 2006)

Hylobates syndactylus.text: Hylobates syndactylus is monogamous and highly territorial.

Hylocichla mustelina.text: They may lay eggs in the nest of other yellow-billed cuckoos, or in the nests of other bird species, including Coccyzus erythropthalmus, Turdus americanus, Dumetella carolinensis and Hylocichla mustelina.

Hylopetes fimbriatus.text: Though little specific information is available on Hylopetes fimbriatus, a close relative, H. lepidus, exhibits no specific reproduction time.

Hymenolepis diminuta.text: There is an extremely low chance for each egg to reach reproductive maturity and that is why Hymenolepis diminuta lays so many eggs. Recent studies have been done on the temperature tolerance of Hymenolepis diminuta eggs.

Hymenolepis nana.text: Hymenolepis nana, like all tapeworms, contain both male and female reproductive structures in each proglottid (Roberts and Janovy, 2000).

Hyperolius marmoratus.text: In captivity Hyperolius marmoratus can live at least 4 years 9 months. (Channing, 2001)

Hyperoodon ampullatus.text: Very little information is known about the reproductive cycle of Hyperoodon planifrons, but it probably resembles the cycle of its close relative, Hyperoodon ampullatus, northern bottlenose whales.

Hyperoodon planifrons.text: Very little information is known about the reproductive cycle of Hyperoodon planifrons, but it probably resembles the cycle of its close relative, Hyperoodon ampullatus, northern bottlenose whales.

Hypoderma lineatum.text: The life cycle of Hypoderma lineatum normally spans a year's time. (Jones, 2000; Reina et al., 2000; Scholl, 1993)

Hypogeomys antimena.text: The mating system has not been studied for all nesomyine species, but at least one species, the Malagasy giant rat (Hypogeomys antimena), is known to be monogamous and mate for life. (Sommer, 2000)

Hypoplectrus nigricans.text: Hermaphroditism in ray-finned fishes involves individuals containing ovarian and testicular tissue (synchronous or simultaneous), as in the Hypoplectrus nigricans, as well as individuals that change from one sex to another (sequential).

Hypseleotris compressa.text: Males in Hypseleotris compressa guard the nest.

Hypsignathus monstrosus.text: There are no reports regarding what Hypsignathus monstrosus does with its young.

Hypsypops rubicundus.text: He removes invertebrates and algae with his mouth, sometimes allowing certain elements to remain, as is the case with Hypsypops rubicundus, a species that weeds out all but red algae from the site.

Hystrix brachyura.text: In captivity, Atherurus africanus has been reported to live 23 years, Hystrix brachyura, 21.

Hystrix cristata.text: Much of our knowledge of breeding behavior in Hystrix cristata comes from captive individuals.

I. abeillei.text: There is little information on the average lifespan of I. abeillei individuals.

I. albicauda.text: Little information is available on reproduction in I. albicauda, so the extent of male parental investment is unknown.

I. chrysater.text: World oriole species, individuals of I. chrysater normally attempt to raise one clutch of 2 to 3 eggs per breeding season (Skutch, 1996; Jaramillo and Burke, 1999; but see Ligi and Omland 2007).

I. didactylus.text: There is little information on parental investment in I. didactylus.

I. gularis.text: Altamira orioles (I. gularis), but appear less sturdy.

I. pustulatus.text: There is no published information on lifespan in I. pustulatus.

I. zenkeri.text: There is no information known about the longevity of I. zenkeri.

Ictalurus punctatus.text: Infections in channel catfish (Ictalurus punctatus, Rafinesque) induced by the sporozoan Henneguya (Protozoa: Myxosporidea) result in seven known and diverse disease manifestations.

Icterus galbula.text: Nests are built in the mid to upper levels of a tree or bush (Howell and Webb, 1995) and are generally similar to the nests of the closely related Icterus galbula (Omland, K.E. personal observation).

Icterus icterus.text: Thus, this falcon is one of a few species of birds that are "obligate nest pirates" (also see South American troupials, Icterus icterus).

Ictinaetus malayensis.text: Parents will sometimes inadvertently care for birds from other nests, including the young of black eagles (Ictinaetus malayensis) and hamerkops (Scopus umbretta). ("Storks (Ciconiidae)", 2003; Campbell, 1974; Perring and Middleton, 1985; Thompson, 1964)

Idiacanthus fasciola.text: Idiacanthus fasciola is an oviparous species with external fertilization.

Idiurus macrotis.text: It is believed to be similar to Idiurus macrotis and other Anomaluridae.

Idiurus zenkeri.text: There is little information on reproduction in Idiurus zenkeri.

Inia geoffrensis.text: The rather long periods of lactation and calving observed in Inia geoffrensis signify a strong mother-calf bond.

Inimicus japonicus.text: An exception to this is Inimicus japonicus, which lays larger, single eggs.

Ischnura gemina.text: Ischnura gemina oviposits in tandem, which is unusual in that the male possesses a "scoop" on his penis.

Isoodon macrourus.text: Male bandicoots don't play a signifacant role in the care of juvenile Isoodon macrourus.

Isostichopus badionotus.text: Isostichopus badionotus have separate sexes and possess a reproductive system consisting of a single gonad and either an oviduct or a vas deferens.

J. jaculus.text: Not much is known about the mating system of J. jaculus because they are solitary and nocturnal.

J. orientalis.text: They crawl with their forelimbs in the same fashion as J. orientalis.

Jaculus blanfordi.text: Based on data from other members of the genus and from a few available collected specimens of Jaculus blanfordi, the gestation period is believed to be approximately forty days long.

Jaculus jaculus.text: Young reach independence at 8 to 10 weeks, and become sexually mature at 8 to 12 months. ("BBC - Nature Wildfacts", 2002; Happold, 1967) Jaculus jaculus bred in captivity do not survive.

Japanese martens.text: Information on mating behaviors of Japanese martens is unavailable.

Junonia coenia.text: Junonia coenia does not live a long time.

K. lanosa.text: No information is available on K. lanosa for this category.

Kathrina tunicata.text: Kathrina tunicata, like all chitons, has seperate sexes.

Kobus megaceros.text: Kobus megaceros has a harem mating system where only the dominant male is sexually active.

L. capensis.text: Maximum intraspecies nucleotides divergences were 1.3% in L. capensis, 2.7% in L. castroviejoi, and 2.3% in L. granatensis but 13.0% in L. europaeus.

L. crassicaudata.text: There is no information available on the parental investment of L. crassicaudata.

L. cyanellus.text: It is thought that L. cyanellus may produce the same number of eggs as Lepomis macrochirus, which is roughly 50,000.

L. guildingii.text: For L. guildingii, the peak was in mid-summer in Australia (December).

L. lagurus.text: Although data are unavailable for L. lagurus, weaning probably occurs after 12 to 14 days as in Lemmus lemmus.

L. leucopus.text: It is not known how long L. leucopus lives in the wild, and it does not survive well in captivity, with the longest record being two years.

L. rosalia.text: Lifespan in this species has not been reported, but in another member of the same genus, L. rosalia, one individual lived in captivity for over 28 years (Nowak, 1999).

L. saxatilis.text: L. saxatilis frequently does not survive its first year.

L. septentrionalis.text: It is likely that L. septentrionalis has a similar potential lifespan.

L. townsendii.text: Female L. townsendii nurse and care for their young for about 1 month.

L.cinereus.text: Females generally give birth to one two two pups per litter, but in some species in the genus Lasiurus, litter sizes may reach 3 or 4 individuals (e.g. Lasiurus borealis, L.seminolus, and L.cinereus). (Hill and Smith, 1984; Nowak, 1991)

L.seminolus.text: Females generally give birth to one two two pups per litter, but in some species in the genus Lasiurus, litter sizes may reach 3 or 4 individuals (e.g. Lasiurus borealis, L.seminolus, and L.cinereus). (Hill and Smith, 1984; Nowak, 1991)

Labridae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Lagenorhynchus.text: There is some information on reproduction in other memebers of the genus Lagenorhynchus.

Lagenorhynchus australis.text: The oldest recorded specimen of Lagenorhynchus australis was thirteen years old. (Goodall et al., 1997a; Goodall et al., 1997b)

Lagenorhynchus cruciger.text: The lifespan of Lagenorhynchus cruciger is not known, however it may be similar to other species within its genus.

Lagenorynchus.text: Little is known bout the mating system of these animals. In general it has been noted that species within the genus Lagenorynchus have gestation periods of ten to twelve months.

Lagopus leucurus.text: The reproductive season of Lagopus leucurus begins in early spring when males display within groups; later, they disperse to their own breeding territories at higher elevations.

Lagostrophus fasciatus.text: The number of partners and size groups formed by Lagostrophus fasciatus in mating are unknown.

Lagurus lagurus.text: One source lists the maximum longevity for Lagurus lagurus as 3.8 years.

Lama glama.text: The product of crossing a Lama glama and an alpaca is a Huarizo, which shows intermediate physical characteristics.

Lama guanicoe.text: This behavior is similar to that of Lama guanicoe: young males that are driven out of the breeding harem may congregate in herds until they are old enough to breed, at which time they will seek out existing harems to take over.

Lama pacos.text: The longevity of Lama pacos in the wild is 5 to 10 years, whereas in captivity it is approximately 20 years. (Ley and Ley, 2006)

Lamprotornis nitens.text: Occasionally northeastern birds will occupy the nests of white-browed sparrow weavers (Plocepasser mahali) and glossy starlings (Lamprotornis nitens).

Lampsilis cardium.text: Lampsilis cardium is a long-term brooder.

Lampsilis fasciola.text: The eggs are internally fertilized in the suprabranchial chambers, then pass into water tubes of the gills, where they develop into glochidia. In the Huron River in Michigan, Lampsilis fasciola was gravid throughout the year.

Lampsilis siliquoidea.text: The eggs are internally fertilized in the suprabranchial chambers, then pass into water tubes of the gills, where they develop into glochidia. Lampsilis siliquoidea is a long-term brooder, and was gravid from early August to late July in the Huron River, Michigan.

Lampyris noctiluca.text: Lampyris noctiluca is the only known example of hormonal influence on sex determination in insects.

Larus argentatus.text: The oxygen consumption (MO2) of Larus modestus is 66% that of Larus argentatus; the oxygen conductance (GO2) is equivalent to 48% of that obtained in 5 other bird species.

Larus glaucescens.text: Larus glaucescens nests in large colonies, especially in Alaska, but also in smaller colonies to the south.

Larus ridibundus.text: Research has shown that Larus ridibundus is a philopatric species in which individuals are inclined to return to breed in the subcolony in which they were born.

Lasiorhinus latifrons.text: The main limit on the lifespan of Lasiorhinus latifrons is the amount of rainfall in a season rather than predation (Wells, 1987).

Lasiurus borealis.text: Females generally give birth to one two two pups per litter, but in some species in the genus Lasiurus, litter sizes may reach 3 or 4 individuals (e.g. Lasiurus borealis, L.seminolus, and L.cinereus). (Hill and Smith, 1984; Nowak, 1991)

Lasiurus intermedius.text: Lasiurus intermedius breeds in late fall; however, fertilization and embryo development do not occur until the following spring (specifically referred to as "delayed fertilization").

Lasmigona complanata.text: Lasmigona complanata is a long-term brooder.

Lasmigona compressa.text: Lasmigona compressa is a long-term brooder.

Laterallus ruber.text: Information on reproduction is unavailable on Laterallus ruber.

Lates calcarifer.text: Lates calcarifer is serially hermaphroditic with males reaching maturity at 37 to 72 cm and changing into females starting at 73 cm, at around five years, three to five years, or six to eight years depending on the source (Moore, 1979, FAO, 1999; Guiguen, 1993).

Latrodectus mactans.text: In addition, the female Latrodectus mactans can store a lifetime supply of sperm to fertilize all the eggs she will ever produce.

Lavia frons.text: The young Lavia frons hangs from its mother and practices flapping its wings until it begins flying by itself.

Leiostomus xanthurus.text: During the fall to early winter months, Leiostomus xanthurus moves offshore to spawn in the shallow to middle-shelf waters.

Lemmiscus curtatus.text: Information on lifespan in Lemmiscus curtatus is not available.

Lemmus lemmus.text: Although data are unavailable for L. lagurus, weaning probably occurs after 12 to 14 days as in Lemmus lemmus.

Lemur catta.text: Lemur catta mates from mid April to June and gives birth in August or September.

Lentipes concolor.text: An example of visual cues is well illustrated by the Lentipes concolor, which is found in the Hawaiian Islands.

Leontopithecus chrysomelas.text: Leontopithecus chrysomelas is a seasonal breeder.

Leontopithecus chrysopygus.text: Most cases have found Leontopithecus chrysopygus to be monogamous when mating but there has been some polyandy observed in certain populations.

Lepidosiren paradoxa.text: Lepidosiren paradoxa breed during the rainy months when adults are able to move into areas that have been flooded and build nests (Alves-Gomes et al., 2003).

Lepilemur leucopus.text: Lepilemur leucopus young are raised entirely by their mother.

Lepisosteus osseus.text: Spawning occurs in the spring and summer for Lepisosteus osseus.

Lepisosteus platyrhincus.text: In Lepisosteus platyrhincus, groups of both sexes congregate in shallow weedy waters where the females place their adhesive eggs among aquatic plants.

Lepomis cyanellus.text: Spawning occurs in Lepomis cyanellus when the water rises above 21 degrees Celsius (70 degrees Fahrenheit).

Lepomis macrochirus.text: Pumpkinseeds maintain larger territories than Lepomis macrochirus but they will sometimes build their nests among Lepomis macrochirus and other sunfish nests and the different species will interbreed.

Leptodea fragilis.text: Leptodea fragilis is a long-term brooder.

Leptonycteris curasoae.text: Little is known about the reproductive behavior of Leptonycteris curasoae.

Leptonycteris nivalis.text: Some studies have shown that Leptonycteris nivalis may have two breeding peaks a year, one in spring and one in September.

Leptoptilos crumeniferus.text: Leptoptilos crumeniferus is known as a colonial breeder.

Lepus alleni.text: Only 2 copulations have been observed, so mating behavior is not well known for Lepus alleni.

Lepus californicus.text: Breeding season for Lepus californicus extends from December through September in Arizona and from late January to August in California and Kansas.

Lepus callotis.text: The breeding season of Lepus callotis is a minimum of 18 weeks, occurring from mid-April to mid-August.

Lepus capensis.text: Lepus capensis newborn weigh an average of 4.5 oz and develop rapidly in the nest.

Lepus castroviejoi.text: There is no information on reproduction available for Lepus castroviejoi.

Lepus europaeus.text: The breeding season for Lepus europaeus is between midwinter (January/February) and midsummer.

Lepus nigricollis.text: Young Lepus nigricollis, called leverets, are precocial at birth.

Lepus othus.text: Lepus othus, in contrast to many other hares, has only one litter per year.

Lepus townsendii.text: Lepus townsendii lives to approximately 8 years of age in the wild. (Wilson and Ruff, 1999)

Lernaeocera branchialis.text: Lernaeocera branchialis is only 2 to 3 mm long at this point and is still resembles a Copepoda.

Lestodelphys halli.text: There is little available information on the longevity of Lestodelphys halli.

Libytheana bachmanii.text: Libytheana bachmanii go from the larva stage to adult in approximately fifteen to seventeen days.

Ligumia nasuta.text: Ligumia nasuta is a long-term brooder.

Ligumia recta.text: Ligumia recta is a long-term brooder.

Liomys irroratus.text: Little is known about the breeding habits of Liomys irroratus.

Lironeca ovalis.text: Cymothoidae, Lironeca ovalis is likely a protandrous, hermaphroditic gill parasite.

Litocranius walleri.text: The mating ritual of Litocranius walleri is complex.

Littorina lirrorea.text: Some Littorina spp. (e.g. Littorina lirrorea, Littorina neritoides) have pelagic capsules extruded from an ovipositor situated near the genital aperture in a position comparable to that of the penis.

Littorina neritoides.text: Some Littorina spp. (e.g. Littorina lirrorea, Littorina neritoides) have pelagic capsules extruded from an ovipositor situated near the genital aperture in a position comparable to that of the penis.

Littorina spp..text: Some Littorina spp. (e.g. Littorina lirrorea, Littorina neritoides) have pelagic capsules extruded from an ovipositor situated near the genital aperture in a position comparable to that of the penis.

Loligo opalescens.text: Most Loligo opalescens live 1-1 1/2 years, but some individuals may live as long as 2-3 years.

Lonchophylla thomasi.text: Very little is known regarding the mating systems of Lonchophylla thomasi. While very little has been discovered regarding the reproductive behavior of Lonchophylla thomasi, some information is available about Phyllostomids in general.

Lonchorhina aurita.text: Lonchorhina aurita mates either at the end of the rainy season or at the begining of the dry season (Fleming, et al.

Lontra felina.text: Lontra felina is most likely a monogamous species.

Lontra provocax.text: Most Lontra provocax only live a few years (Chanin, 1985).

Lophiomys imhausi.text: Young Lophiomys imhausi are relatively precocial; they are covered with hair at birth and grow quickly.

Loxigilla portoricensis.text: The bananaquit (Coereba flaveola portoricensis), Puerto Rican bullfinch (Loxigilla portoricensis) and Puerto Rican tody (Todus mexicanus) are all birds which share nests with E. coqui.

Loxodonta africana.text: Data from the previously recognized inclusive species, African elephants (Loxodonta africana) suggests lifespans of 65 to 70 years old in the wild.

Loxodonta cyclotis.text: There are no reports of lifespan in Loxodonta cyclotis.

Luidia ciliaris.text: The sexual reproduction of Luidia ciliaris is similar to the reproduction of most other starfish.

Lutra lutra.text: Lutra lutra has a continuous breeding cycle and female otters have a continuous estrus cycle.

Lycaena rubidus.text: Lycaena rubidus is inactive during the chrysalis stage and avoids predation by using camouflage.

Lycaon pictus.text: Lycaon pictus reaches sexual maturity at approximately 12 to 18 months, though they usually do not mate until much later.

Lyncodon patagonicus.text: Parental care in Lyncodon patagonicus is as unknown as the rest of the species' reproductive behavior.

M brevicaudata.text: There is relatively little known about the mating patterns of M brevicaudata in particular.

M. albicaudatus.text: The lifespan of M. albicaudatus is not known in the wild, but it is approximately six years in captivity.

M. alfari.text: M. alfari, a closely related species, breeds at least from late April to June, and this may also be the case with Microsciurus flaviventer.

M. americana.text: Little is known about the lifespan of M. americana.

M. auriculus.text: In their close relatives, ovulation and fertilization do not occur until the following spring, and it is likely that M. auriculus is similar.

M. australasica.text: There has not been sufficient research on the lifespan of M. australasica, but average lifespan has been reported at 20 years with a maximum recorded age of 26 years.

M. australis.text: The oldest recorded age of M. australis is five and a half years.

M. avellanarius.text: Little is known about the longevity of M. avellanarius in the wild, but research suggests that individuals live an average of 3 years, at the end of which their teeth show heavy wear.

M. bennettii.text: Close relatives of the species M. bennettii give birth to a single offspring at the beginning of the wet season, which immediately follows the end of the dry season.

M. bidens.text: The is no data on the lifespan in M. bidens.

M. bowdoini.text: The only information on the reproductive system of M. bowdoini is from occasional observations of young.

M. brevicaudata.text: There has been no specific research done on the parental investment for M. brevicaudata.

M. canescens.text: There is little information regarding the lifespan of M. canescens.

M. crassicaudata.text: However, a con-generic species, M. crassicaudata produced one specimen which lived in captivity for almost 20 years.

M. crinifrons.text: This implies that M. crinifrons may have a lifespan similar to the 10-12 year lifespan estimated for Muntiacus reevesi. (Dueling and Myers, 2004; Lu and Sheng, 1984)

M. cyclopis.text: It is reasonable to assume that M. cyclopis is like other members of the genus in this respect.

M. cyclotis.text: There is no information reported for parental investment in M. cyclotis.

M. dorsalis.text: Weaning occurs in M. dorsalis between 10 and 12 months of age, and the young become more or less independent at that time.

M. dryas.text: The specific parental investment and care patterns for M. dryas are not known.

M. erminea.text: If reproduction in M. katiah is similar to that in M. erminea then young are blind and helpless at birth but increase in size rapidly until about 8 weeks of age, when they are capable of hunting on their own.

M. evotis.text: Parental investment is not well known for M. evotis.

M. feae.text: Young M. feae stay with their mother until they reach maturity.

M. flaviventer.text: There are no data available on the lifespan of M. flaviventer.

M. foina.text: Copulation of M. foina may occur midsummer, but implantation does not occur until early in the following spring.

M. fuscata.text: It is reasonable to assume that M. fuscata is like other members of the genus in terms of longevity.

M. fuscus.text: There is little known about the lifespan of M. fuscus although other captive Moschus have been found to live up to 20 years in captivity.

M. gongshanensis.text: The lifespan of M. gongshanensis is unknown.

M. grayi.text: There is no information on the lifespan of M. grayi and there have been no reports of attempts to keep any animals in captivity.

M. guentheri.text: However, other voles are known to live an average of less than one month (Microtus pennsylvanicus) to a maximum in captivity of nearly four years (M. guentheri). (Nowak, 1999)

M. javanensis.text: No research on reproductive habits has been conducted for either Mydaus marchei or M. javanensis.

M. katiah.text: The mating system and behavior of M. katiah is unknown.

M. keenii.text: Little information on the longevity of M. keenii is available.

M. kunsi.text: Since M. kunsi are in the infraclass Metatheria (marsupial mammals), they almost certainly have a short gestation period and young fairly undeveloped at birth, as these traits generally characterize this group of animals. (Anderson, 1982; Salazar et al., 1994)

M. layardii.text: There have been no studies of parental care in M. layardii.

M. leonina.text: The gestation period of female M. leonina is about eight months.

M. leucophaeus.text: Males in some species care for the young on occasion, and may do so in M. leucophaeus.

M. longicaudata.text: Information on the reproductive behaviors of M. longicaudata is not available.

M. lucifugus.text: The lifespan of M. lucifugus is extended by their ability to find food and inhabit a variety of roosts.

M. meles.text: M. meles and A. collaris have lived in captivity 16 and 13 years, respectively.

M. nadicaudatus.text: The maximum lifespan of M. nadicaudatus is three to four years (Nowak, 1997)

M. personata.text: Beyond this virtually nothing is known about the reproductive cycle and life history of M. personata (Pei & Wang 1995).

M. prehensilis.text: There is no available information on the lifespan of M. prehensilis, but G. ingrahami can reach the age of 6 years in the wild. (Clough, 1974)

M. pusillus.text: The lifespan of M. pusillus is undocumented.

M. reevesi.text: The gestation period is not known for M. crinifrons, but in M. reevesi gestation lasts 209-220 days.

M. rutilus.text: Litters of M. rutilus range from 1 to 9, although litters are commonly of 6 to 8 young.

M. ruwenzorii.text: No information regarding lifespan of M. ruwenzorii is available.

M. schreibersi.text: Although no reports were found for M. australis, newborn M. schreibersi weigh between 2 nd 3 g. Weaning of M. schreibersi occurs at about 2 months of age.

M. schreibersii.text: Miniopterus australis, like M. schreibersii, chooses specific sites for nurseries in which to rear young.

M. silenus.text: Groups of M. silenus typically contain one male and several females and juveniles.

M. sinica.text: Although there is a well developed dominance hierarchy among troops of M. sinica, copulation frequency is not higher among the dominant males.

M. sphinx.text: Gestation length has not been reported for this species, but is known to be 168 to 176 days in M. sphinx, and is probably similar for M. leucophaeus.

M. stejnegeri.text: Nothing is known about the reproduction of M. stejnegeri, although it is speculated that litter size is one and parturition occurs in the spring and summer.

M. suilla.text: There is little information on parental investment in M. suilla.

M. tridactyla.text: The mating system of M. tridactyla is not known.

M. tuberculata.text: The time of mating and details of the reproductive cycle are not known, although mating by M. tuberculata occurs sometime between February and April.

M. xanthognathus.text: It is not known if the young of M. xanthognathus stay in the nest longer than do the young of these other species of Microtus.

M. zibellina.text: M. zibellina reach sexual maturity in their second year of life (Walker, 1995).

Macaca fuscata.text: There is period in which juvenile males are solitary, as in Macaca fuscata and Macaca mulatta.

Macaca mulatta.text: There is period in which juvenile males are solitary, as in Macaca fuscata and Macaca mulatta.

Macaca silenus.text: Macaca silenus has no specific breeding season.

Macroglossus minimus.text: The closely related Macroglossus minimus is better known.

Macroglossus sobrinus.text: The estimated lifespan for Macroglossus sobrinus is 4 to 6 years.

Macropus eugenii.text: The gestation period of Macropus eugenii lasts 25 to 28 days.

Macropus fuliginosus.text: In Experiment 1, 11 lactating western grey kangaroos (Macropus fuliginosus) received injections either of saline (n = 2) or of bromocriptine at dose rates of 0.2, 1.0 or 5.0 mg kg-1 bodyweight (n = 3 per dose).

Macropus parryi.text: Unlike some other species of wallaby, in which a mother forceably removes her young when the time is right, the young Macropus parryi leaves the protective pouch on its own.

Macropus rufus.text: Macropus rufus has a short gestation period.

Macrotarsomys bastardi.text: Macrotarsomys bastardi tend to live in pairs.

Magicicada septendecim.text: The17-year life cycle of Magicicada septendecim is of critical importance to its reproductive behavior.

Makaira nigricans.text: In the South Atlantic, Makaira nigricans exhibits fall spawning when the sea surface temperature is at 28C.

Malacanthidae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Malaclemys.text: While all turtles reproduce by eggs, the genus Malaclemys usually does not produce more than 4-8 eggs in a clutch.

Malagasy herpestids.text: If G. fasciata is like other Malagasy herpestids, specifically Mungotictis decemlineata, the young may remain with the mother until sexually mature, around the age of 2 years.

Malapterurus electricus.text: Nothing much is known of the reproductive biology of Malapterurus electricus According to Polle & Gosse (1969), breeding pairs nest in holes some 3 meters in length excavated in clay banks in water 1 to 3 meters deep.

Mandrillus sphinx.text: Mandrillus sphinx reaches sexual maturity around the age of 3.5 years.

Manis crassicaudata.text: The longevity of Manis crassicaudata under captive conditions is greater than 13 years.

Manis tricuspis.text: At birth, the young of Manis tricuspis weigh between 90-159 grams.

Manouria emys.text: Unlike most tortoises, females of Manouria emys do invest in their offspring after they lay their eggs.

Manta birostris.text: The gestation period of Manta birostris is 13 months, after which females give birth to 1 or 2 live young.

Mantella aurantiaca.text: Mantella aurantiaca typically has a life span of 8 years.

Marcopus rufogriseus.text: In at least one species (Marcopus rufogriseus), extended associations between females and their independent young are known to reduce the success of future reproduction. (Clutton-Brock, 1991; Nowak, 1991; Vaughan, Ryan, and Czaplewski, 2000)

Margaritifera margaritifera.text: The record for a Margaritifera margaritifera was over 200 years (Bauer, 2001a).

Marmosa robinsoni.text: In related species belonging to the genus Marmosa, such as Marmosa robinsoni, life expectancy is typically under 1 year of age in the wild and up to 3 years in captivity (Nowak, 1991). (Nowak, 1991)

Marmosops incanus.text: The limited breeding season shown by Marmosops incanus indicates that the female are monoestric and that the estrous cycle is short.

Marmota.text: Although there are not data specifically relating to red marmots, other members of the genus Marmota can live between 13 and 15 years.

Marmota bobak.text: The exact lifespan of Marmota bobak in the wild is unknown, although captive marmots may live as long as 15 years. (Armatige, 1975)

Marmota camtschatica.text: Since females cannot accumulate enough resources to support annual reproduction, female Marmota camtschatica will skip reproduction and reproduce only every other year (Macdonald 2001).

Marmota marmota.text: Marmota marmota mates within the first few days after emergence from hibernation, which occurs in May.

Martes martes.text: In the wild, male and female Martes martes may mate in their first summer, at 14 months of age.

Martes melampus.text: Martes melampus reach sexual maturity between one and two years of age.

Martes zibellina.text: For example, Martes zibellina have an average litter size of 2.2, but can give birth to anywhere from 1 to 7 pups.

Masticophis flagellum.text: In the U.S. Masticophis flagellum reproduces once per year.

Megachile latimanus.text: Megachile latimanus females lay their eggs on the larval food supply so as to guarantee the larvae will be able to grow.

Megadyptes antipodes.text: When Megadyptes antipodes mates, the male mounts the female and rests his neck on the back of hers and vibrates his flippers along her sides. Megadyptes antipodes begins its breeding season in August with the selection of mates and nest sites.

Megalops atlanticus.text: Megalops atlanticus is known to have a very long lifespan.

Megapodius spp..text: Species that use clumped geothermal incubation sites may aggregate in large numbers (over 50,000) onto communal incubation sites. Megapodius spp., Eulipoa wallacei, and perhaps Talegalla are thought to exhibit female-defense monogamy.

Melanosuchus niger.text: Melanosuchus niger - pods were found to occur in areas of deeper water than -C. crocodilus-, implying choice of nesting sites in lower-lying areas (Britton 1999, Da Silveira et al 1997, Herron 1990, Thorbjarnarson 1998).

Meleagris gallopavo.text: Work done in 1979 by Sugihara and Heston suggests that ocellated turkeys have a similar social system to that of American wild turkeys (Meleagris gallopavo), in which males do not generally provide parental care.

Meles meles.text: Other badgers (Meles meles and Arctonyx collaris) breed annually.

Mellisuga helenae.text: The size of hummingbird eggs range from 8 by 11 mm in bee hummingbirds (Mellisuga helenae) to 12 by 20 mm in giant hummingbirds (Patagona gigas).

Mellita quinquiesperforata.text: The average lifespan of Mellita quinquiesperforata is four years, but they have been known to survive for up to ten years. (McHenry, 1998)

Melogale everetti.text: There appears to be no information on the lifespan of Melogale everetti either in the wild or in captivity.

Melogale moschata.text: However, a very similar species, Melogale moschata, the Chinese ferret badger, is said to have still been living after 10 years and 6 months in captivity. (Nowak, 1995)

Melursus ursinus.text: Information on the reproductive behavior of Melursus ursinus varies.

Menidia clarkhubbsi.text: Finally, unisexuality (egg development occurring with or without fertilization) can also occur in a variety of forms, and usually involves some male involvement, although at least ones species (Menidia clarkhubbsi) appears to utilize true parthenogenesis – females produce only female offspring with no participation from males.

Menippe mercenaria.text: Most female Menippe mercenaria sexually mature around two years old, and are most likely to breed between the spring and fall.

Mephitis macroura.text: Breeding in Mephitis macroura occurs from the middle of February to the end of March.

Mephitis mephitis.text: During the mating season, males of some species may monopolize several females (e.g. Mephitis mephitis), chasing other males away when they approach.

Meriones libycus.text: The exact processes involved in the reproduction of Meriones libycus in the wild are not well documented.

Mesoplodon.text: The litter size is most likely one offspring per birth in the entire genus Mesoplodon.

Mesoplodon carlhubbsi.text: There is not much data available on reproduction in Mesoplodon carlhubbsi.

Mesoplodon europaeus.text: As with all cetaceans, the young are necessarily precocial at birth and Mesoplodon europaeus are about 2.1 m long at birth.

Mesoplodon grayi.text: Mesoplodon grayi, like many whales, are most often seen in pods and highly social behavior has been observed.

Mesoplodon perrini.text: Since Mesoplodon perrini is such an elusive species, as is typical of this genus, nothing is known about its longevity and life history.

Microcavia australis.text: Microcavia australis males become very aggressive during mating in the wild.

Microcebus coquereli.text: Microcebus coquereli reach sexual maturity at 9 months.

Microcebus murinus.text: Microcebus murinus reproduce between September and March.

Microcerculus philomela.text: Very little is known about the nesting habits of Microcerculus philomela due to their secretive nature.

Microdipodops pallidus.text: The lifespan of Microdipodops pallidus is approximately 5.5 years.

Microgale dobsoni.text: When Microgale dobsoni was trapped in the wild during the month of April, no lactating females were captured and none of the animals were fully adult.

Microgale talazaci.text: Microgale talazaci is primarily solitary, but a male and female will sometimes form a stable relationship which lasts throughout the year.

Microhierax caerulescens.text: Two species of falconids, red-throated caracaras (Daptrius americanus) and collared falconets (Microhierax caerulescens) regularly breed cooperatively.

Microlophus albemarlensis.text: Microlophus albemarlensis can live up to 10 years. (Jackson, 1985)

Micromys minutus.text: In captivity, Micromys minutus can live to be just under 5 years old. (Burton 1969; Grzimek 1990; Nowak 1993)

Micropotamogale lamottei.text: The lifespan of Micropotamogale lamottei is not known.

Micropterus dolomieu.text: Parental care in Micropterus dolomieu is the sole responsibility of the male, who guards the eggs and fry for an extended length of time (Cooke et al., 2003a).

Micropterus salmoides.text: For example, common species, such as the Perca fluviatilis (aka Perca fluviatilis) and Micropterus salmoides can live 25 and 15 to 24 years respectively.

Microsciurus flaviventer.text: One female Microsciurus flaviventer was found to have two embryos (Nowak, 1999).

Microtus californicus.text: Ovulation in Microtus californicus is induced by copulation.

Microtus chrotorrhinus.text: Microtus chrotorrhinus breeds from early spring until late fall (Hamilton 1943).

Microtus oeconomus.text: Various mating systems have been observed in Microtus oeconomus, including promiscuous, multi-partner groups, polygyny, and monogamy.

Microtus pennsylvanicus.text: Mating in Microtus pennsylvanicus is promiscuous.

Microtus richardsoni.text: Jannett (1979) observed a captive group of Microtus richardsoni to have induced estrus.

Microtus sp..text: Microtus sp., in general, appear to have a fairly plastic reproductive biology where the emphasis seems to be on the ability to produce the correct response (phenotypic) given the ecological conditions in which the population finds itself.

Micrurus fulvius.text: Micrurus fulvius breeds from late spring early summer and late summer to early fall.

Millipora alcicornis.text: The overgrowth of the sea fan by other organisms is also another leading cause of death, especially by the hydrocoralline Millipora alcicornis and some encrusting bryozoa.

Milvus migrans.text: Wild records are unavailable, but related Milvus migrans have been recorded living up to 24 years in the wild. (Richards, 1998)

Miniopterus australis.text: Miniopterus australis, like M. schreibersii, chooses specific sites for nurseries in which to rear young.

Miopithecus talapoin.text: Miopithecus talapoin has lived 28 years in captivity (Haltenorth and Diller, 1988).

Mirounga leonina.text: Southern elephant seals (Mirounga leonina) demonstrate extreme polygyny, wherein males fight for exclusive access to harems of females.

Misumena vatia.text: Misumena vatia females are larger then the males.

Mitsukurina owstoni.text: Though there are no data for Mitsukurina owstoni in particular, sharks in general do not provide any degree of parental investment.

Mnemiopsis leidyi.text: When food is plentiful and the water temperature is between 19-23°C, Mnemiopsis leidyi will spawn.

Mniotilta varia.text: Mniotilta varia typically breeds between April and August.

Moloch horridus.text: There is not much information on the mating system in Moloch horridus.

Molothrus ater.text: Males and females protect their young against nest predation and nest parasitism by brown-headed cowbirds (Molothrus ater). (Mostrom, Curry, and Lohr, 2002)

Momotus momota.text: Instead of beginning its tunnel in an exposed soil surface, Momotus momota prefers to start from the side of some pit or hollow in the ground, such as the den of a burrowing animal, or a hole dug by man.

Monachus tropicalis.text: Very little is known about the reproductive behavior of Monachus tropicalis.

Moniliformis moniliformis.text: Moniliformis moniliformis is a dioecious species.

Monodelphis brevicaudata.text: There is no information about the specific parental investment of Monodelphis brevicaudata.

Monodelphis kunsi.text: The lifespan of Monodelphis kunsi is unknown.

Monodon monoceros.text: Upon reaching the captive establishment, Monodon monoceros have only survived from 1 to 4 months.

Morone americana.text: Morone americana is polyandrous, without mate guarding or displays of dominance.

Morone chrysops.text: Spawning of Morone chrysops occurs as early as mid-February in the southern United States and as late as May in the more northern latitudes, or whenever water temperatures reach about 14-20 degrees celsius.

Moschus chrysogaster.text: The average lifespan of wild caught captive Moschus chrysogaster is about 7 years.

Moschus moschiferus.text: In Moschus moschiferus, males scent mark and defend a territory during breeding season.

Motacilla alba.text: The longest recorded lifespan is a 9 year, 11 month old white wagtail (Motacilla alba).

Mugil cephalus.text: Mugil cephalus are isochronal spawners, with all oocytes reaching maturity at the same time.

Muncgotictis decemlineata.text: Although other details on the reproduction of G. grandidieri are lacking, other species of mongoose on Madagascar have gestation lengths of 72 to 92 days (Galidia elegans) and 90-105 days (Muncgotictis decemlineata).

Mungotictis decemlineata.text: If G. fasciata is like other Malagasy herpestids, specifically Mungotictis decemlineata, the young may remain with the mother until sexually mature, around the age of 2 years.

Muntiacus crinifrons.text: The lifespan of Muntiacus crinifrons is not well known.

Muntiacus feae.text: Muntiacus feae, like other muntjacs, has a relatively short lifespan compared to other cervids.

Muntiacus reevesi.text: This implies that M. crinifrons may have a lifespan similar to the 10-12 year lifespan estimated for Muntiacus reevesi. (Dueling and Myers, 2004; Lu and Sheng, 1984)

Murina cyclotis.text: A related species Murina cyclotis was documented on the Malay Peninsula carrying 2 fetuses, so twins may occur occasionally. ("Biodiversity Information Sharing Service (BISS)", 2006; Nowak, 1999)

Mus musculus.text: Wild-derived captive Mus musculus individuals have lived up to 4 years in captivity.

Mustela.text: Longevity hs not been reported for this species, but for similarly sized members of the genus Mustela, there is very little variation in longevity.

Mustela altaica.text: The Mustela altaica averages 8.7 pups per litter, but can have between 3 and 14 young in a single bout of reproduction.

Mustela kathiah.text: Little is known about reproductive behavior of Mustela kathiah.

Mustela nivalis.text: Carnivores may have two or three litters per year (as with Mustela nivalis), but most carnivore females have just one litter every one to two years.

Mustela sibirica.text: The weaning age for Mustela sibirica is 56 days and sexual maturity is reached at about 2 years of age.

Mydaus marchei.text: The mating system and behavior of Mydaus marchei is not known. No research on reproductive habits has been conducted for either Mydaus marchei or M. javanensis.

Myliobatis californicus.text: Only a few species, like Myliobatis californicus with its nearly year-long gestation period, are known to differ from this pattern.

Myocastor coypus.text: The potential longevity of Myocastor coypus is 6 years.

Myodes glareolus.text: The mating system of Myodes glareolus can be described as polygamous (Macdonald 2001), and possibly promiscuous (Horne and Ylonen 1998).

Myotis.text: Life span in Myotis is usually 6 to 7 years, but Myotis myotis were recorded as 13 years old in the United Kingdom.

Myotis austroriparious.text: Myotis austroriparious is the only species of Myotis known to give birth to twin young.

Myotis austroriparius.text: Myotis austroriparius colonies are usually between 2,000 and 90,000 individuals.

Myotis californicus.text: There is little documented information available on reproduction and ontongeny in Myotis californicus.

Myotis evotis.text: Myotis evotis reproduces once per year, and females may form maternity colonies of 5 to 30 individuals in the summer (colonies may contain a few males), or they can remain solitary.

Myotis myotis.text: These roosts may be shared with bats of other species, including greater mouse-eared bats, Myotis myotis, and Geoffroy’s bats, Myotis emarginatus, but the species do not roost in the same parts of the roost structure.

Myotis leibii.text: The lifespan of Myotis leibii is thought to be between 6-12 years, however they have a low survival rate (0.757 for males and 0.421 for females).

Myotis lucifigus.text: The longest-lived bat on record is a little brown bat (Myotis lucifigus).

Myotis lucifugus.text: Reproduction in Myotis lucifugus involves copulation and insemination prior to hibernation.

Myotis emarginatus.text: These roosts may be shared with bats of other species, including greater mouse-eared bats, Myotis myotis, and Geoffroy’s bats, Myotis emarginatus, but the species do not roost in the same parts of the roost structure.

Myoxus glis.text: The young of Myoxus glis exit the womb with the hind end first.

Mystacina robusta.text: No information is available about the parental investment of Mystacina robusta.
