Pelea capreolus.text: Mating takes place for Pelea capreolus in April, when males fight over females.

Pelecanoides urinatrix.text: Other aspects of their reproduction are probably similar to Pelecanoides urinatrix. (Brooke, 2004; del Hoyo, Elliott, and Sargatal, 1992)

Pelecanus erythrorhynchos.text: Pelecanus erythrorhynchos, the white pelican, has been recorded to live up to 34 years in captivity. (Terres, 1980)

Pelecanus occidentalis.text: Pelecanus occidentalis, the brown pelican, has been recorded to live up to 31 years in the wild and 29 in captivity.

Pentalagus furnessi.text: Pentalagus furnessi usually mate in November or December.

Penthetor lucasi.text: Research indicates that breeding in Penthetor lucasi is seasonal.

Peponocephala electra.text: Nothing is known about the mating systems of Peponocephala electra or its close relatives. ("MarineBio", 2009; "Melon-Headed Whale - MarineBio.org", 2009; Allen, 2008; Dutton, 1981) Little is known about the reproduction of Peponocephala electra.

Perameles gunnii.text: The reproductive rate for Perameles gunnii is very high.

Perca fluviatilis.text: Perca fluviatilis (aka Perca fluviatilis) and Micropterus salmoides can live 25 and 15 to 24 years respectively.

Perennial monogamy.text: Perennial monogamy, or year-round pair bonding, occurs in at least a dozen avian families, including cockatoos and other parrots (Psittaciformes). (Oring et al., 1982)

Periplaneta americana.text: The development of Periplaneta americana is hemimetabolous, meaning there is no major metamophosis.

Perisoreus canadensis.text: Perisoreus canadensis breeds in coniferous forests and sometimes in mixed coniferous-deciduous woodlands.

Peromyscus.text: It has been shown that in several species of the genus Peromyscus, the male remains with the female to help care for the young, although no data exist for Peromyscus gossypinus. (Nowak, 1999; Wolfe and Linzey, June 1977)

Peromyscus attwateri.text: The average lifespan of the Peromyscus attwateri is 6.8 months, but can live as long as 18 months. (Davis and Schmidly, 1994)

Peromyscus aztecus.text: Peromyscus aztecus breed throughout the year if it is not too cold or too hot.

Peromyscus boylii.text: In a long-term mark-recapture study of Peromyscus boylii in Arizona, Abbott et al. (1999) found that of more than 300 individuals most survived one year or less.

Peromyscus californicus.text: Unlike most mice Peromyscus californicus is truly monogamous, and once mated will stay paired for life (McCade and Blanchard 1950; Ribble 1991; Ribble and Salvioni 1990; Guvernick and Nelson 1990). (McCabe and Blanchard, 1950; Ribble, 1992)

Peromyscus eremicus.text: The penis is nevertheless broad, and its size has been suggested to increase "locking" during 3.5 percent of copulations (Species Information Library Peromyscus eremicus 1994).

Peromyscus gossypinus.text: Peromyscus gossypinus produces at least 4 litters per breeding season.

Peromyscus leucopus.text: In the sister species of cotton mice, Peromyscus leucopus, variation in litter size with latitude has been reported.

Peromyscus maniculatus.text: Consequently, P50 at pH 7.4, PCO2(7.4), the CO2 Bohr effect, and the buffer slope (delta log PCO2/delta pH) were determined via the mixing technique in Peromyscus maniculatus native to a range of altitudes but acclimated to 340 or 3,800 m. PCO2(7.4) and buffer slope were substantially lower at high altitude.

Peromyscus polionotus.text: In some species, like Peromyscus polionotus or Peromyscus californicus, mating appears to be strictly monogamous.

Peropteryx kappleri.text: Reports on the mating systems of Peropteryx kappleri vary as to whether or not females form harems that are monopolized by one or a few males.

Peropteryx macrotis.text: Information about the parental investment of Peropteryx macrotis is unavailable.

Peroryctes raffrayana.text: Peroryctes raffrayana are polyestrous, and usually have a litter of between one and six young.

Petaurista petaurista.text: Because Petaurista petaurista is a nocturnal animal, little is known about its reproductive activities.

Petauroides volans.text: Petauroides volans reach sexual maturity after 2 years, lemuroid ringtail possumss may have a similar pattern. (Baverstock et al., 1990; Burnie and Wilson, 2005; Flannery, 1994; Lindenmayer and Lacy, 1995; Vaughan, Ryan, and Czaplewski, 2000; Winter, 1995)

Petaurus norfolcensis.text: The breeding season in Petaurus norfolcensis occurs during June and July, with a gestation period that lasts slightly less than three weeks (Suckling 1995, Nowak 1999).

Petrogale concinna.text: The maximum known lifespan of Petrogale concinna is 17 years. (Ohio University, 2006)

Petrogale lateralis.text: Very little information is available for Petrogale lateralis; the following account is based primarily on other wallaby species.

Petrogale penicillata.text: There are few details about parental investment in Petrogale penicillata.

Petrogale penicillata inornata.text: The process of birth has been observed on one occasion in the rock-wallaby Petrogale penicillata inornata.

Petrogale xanthopus.text: Given good nutrition and living conditions, Petrogale xanthopus breed all year long.

Petromus typicus.text: The lifespan of Petromus typicus is unknown.

Petropseudes dahli.text: Petropseudes dahli is one of few obligate monogamous marsupial species.

Phacellodomus rufifrons.text: Troupials are well known as nest pirates, seeking and seizing the covered, hanging stick nests of common thornbirds (Phacellodomus rufifrons) or great kiskadees (Pitangus sulphuratus).

Phalanger lullulae.text: Mating behavior has not been observed in Phalanger lullulae.

Phalanger orientalis.text: The gestation period for Phalanger orientalis lasts around 13 days.

Phalaropus lobatus.text: The Phalaropus lobatus females will arrive at the Artic breeding grounds in May to mid-June before the males and will compete among themselves and display in small parties.

Phaner furcifer.text: Dwarf lemurs (Cheirogaleus) have been recorded living up to 23.2 years old and fork-marked lemurs (Phaner furcifer) have been recorded living up to 25 years in captivity.

Pharomachrus moccino.text: More is known about its their close relatives, Pharomachrus moccino.

Phasianus colchicus.text: Marble spleen disease (MSD) of ring-necked pheasants (Phasianus colchicus L.) was transmitted in the laboratory to pheasants and turkeys (Meleagris gallopavo L.) by oral, colonic, and intravenous routes of inoculation, using cell-free supernatant fluids of splenic suspension from birds with naturally occurring MSD.

Phestilla sibogae.text: Phestilla sibogae is a simultaneous hermaphrodite; this means that both male and female reproductive organs are present and mature at the same time.

Philander opossum.text: However, Philander opossum does reproduce throughout the year, but at lower levels during the months of June to August.

Philepitta schlegeli.text: Schlegel’s asities (Philepitta schlegeli) drop their wings, fluff their breast feathers and lift up their tails while squeaking.

Philetairus socius.text: In the wild, these birds commonly breed in the large, communal nests of Philetairus socius.

Phocoenoides dalli dalli.text: Phocoenoides dalli dalli appear to have three major breeding grounds.

Phrynosoma douglassii.text: The mating season for Phrynosoma douglassii extends from April to June.

Phyllobates terribilis.text: The breeding season for Phyllobates terribilis is throughout the rainy season.

Phyllopteryx eques.text: Unlike most fish species, in Phyllopteryx eques the male incubates the eggs.

Phyllostomus hastatus.text: Phyllostomus hastatus may be monoestrus (one reproductive bout per year) or polyestrus (multiple reproductive bouts in a year); the pattern may be geographically dependent.

Pinus strobus.text: Pinus strobus plants become reproductively mature between 5 and 10 years of age, but do not reach peak strobilus production until the age of about 20 years.

Pipa pipa.text: Reproduction in Pipa pipa includes direct development of the young; there is no larval stage.

Pithecia albicans.text: Most species reproduce seasonally and give birth to single offspring, although Pithecia albicans is reported to reproduce throughout the year.

Pitta caerulea.text: Giant pittas (Pitta caerulea) in a zoo lived for more than 12 years. (Erritzoe, 2003)

Pitta moluccensis.text: The oldest recorded pitta in the wild is a blue-winged pitta (Pitta moluccensis) that was recaptured 5.5 years after being banded.

Plethodon serratus.text: There have not been any studies conducted specifically on the courtship behavior of Plethodon serratus.

Prionailurus viverrina.text: The closely related fishing cat (Prionailurus viverrina) has mating peaks in January and February.

Prionodon linsang.text: Although no details are available on the reproductive cycle of Prionodon pardicolor, the estrus cycle for banded linsangs (Prionodon linsang), a related species, is 11 days.

Prionodon pardicolor.text: Although no details are available on the reproductive cycle of Prionodon pardicolor, the estrus cycle for banded linsangs (Prionodon linsang), a related species, is 11 days.

Procyon cancrivorus.text: Procyon cancrivorus undoubtedly falls within this range of variation.

Procyon lotor.text: In 1982, a Procyon lotor was still surviving in a zoo after 20 years and seven months. (De La Rosa and Nocke, 2000; Nowak, 1999)

Profelis aurata.text: Little is known of reproduction in Profelis aurata.

Progne dominicensis.text: No information has been reported about the lifespan of Progne dominicensis.

Propithecus diadema.text: Perrier's sifakas were once considered a subspecies of Propithecus diadema, diademed sifakas, which has been studied more thoroughly.

Propithecus perrieri.text: There are no known Propithecus perrieri in captivity.

Propithecus tattersali.text: Propithecus tattersali mates seasonally, usually in late January through March.

Propithecus verreauxi.text: However, an individual of another species in the genus, Propithecus verreauxi, is reported to have lived beyon 23 years on captivity (Nowak, 1999).

Proptihecus perrieri.text: There are no published reports of parental investment in Proptihecus perrieri.

Proteles cristatus.text: Proteles cristatus forms monogamous mating pairs.

Psephenus herricki.text: Psephenus herricki females lay hundreds or thousands of small, bright yellow eggs on submerged and emergent objects in stream riffles with fast current.

Pseudacris triseriata.text: In Michigan, the breeding season of Pseudacris triseriata begins in mid-March and runs through late May, although most activity occurs in April.

Pseudalopex griseus.text: Studies of Pseudalopex griseus in Patagonia indicate that mating is monogamous, with a mated pair maintaining their territory throughout the year.

Pseudalopex gymnocercus.text: However an individual from a congeneric species, Pseudalopex gymnocercus, lived for 13 years and 8 months in capivity. (Nowak, 1999)

Pseudemys concinna.text: With regards to a closely related species, Pseudemys concinna, the male pursues the female and sniffs her tail after the female releases a pheromone.

Pseudemys rubriventris.text: Pseudemys rubriventris produce one clutch of eggs yearly containing 8 to 22 eggs.

Pseudo-nitzschia.text: While no monoecious clones of Pseudo-nitzschia have been reported, mating between two clones of the same sex has been observed, suggesting that a single culture could switch sex under some conditions which have not yet been investigated, or more than one mating type exists (Davidovich & Bates 1998).

Pseudo-nitzschia calliantha.text: Pseudo-nitzschia calliantha can reproduce asexually through cell division and sexually to restore cell size (Davidovich & Bates 1998).

Pseudo-nitzschia multiseries.text: Pseudo-nitzschia multiseries reproduces asexually through cell division and sexually (Bates & Davidovich 2002).

Pseudo-nitzschia spp..text: Reproduction in P. brasiliana has been reported to be homothallic, which is in contrast to the observations of heterothallic auxosporulation in other Pseudo-nitzschia spp. (Quijano-Scheggia et al. 2009).

Pseudocalyptomena graueri.text: Pseudocalyptomena graueri are thought to have long breeding seasons.

Pseudocheirus herbertensis.text: Although the specific maturation time of Pseudocheirus herbertensis is unknown, for the genera Pseudochirulus, young leave their mother's pouch after 10 weeks.

Pseudochirulus cinereus.text: There is little information on the reproduction in Pseudochirulus cinereus.

Pseudomys higginsi.text: Young Pseudomys higginsi are born in natal fur with a head and body length one-third the size of the mother.

Pseudotriton montanus.text: Pseudotriton montanus has been found to live past 15 years in captivity.

Pteridium aquilinum.text: Observations on the male nucleus during fertilization in the fern Pteridium aquilinum.

Pteromys volans.text: The information on the reproduction of Pteromys volans is contradictory and incomplete.

Pteronura brasiliensis.text: Young Pteronura brasiliensis are weaned 3-4 months after birth.

Pteropus conspicillatus.text: Female Pteropus conspicillatus reach sexual maturity at two years of age.

Pteropus dasymallus.text: Pteropus dasymallus have low reproductive rates.

Pteropus samoensis.text: Pteropus samoensis females give birth to one young per year.

Pteropus tokudae.text: No information has been discerned about the reproductive pattern of Pteropus tokudae.

Pteropus vampyrus.text: The Lubee Foundation has a unique collection of species housed in captivity which includes the largest (1.2 kg, Pteropus vampyrus) and the smallest (180 g, Pteropus pumilus) species of the genus Pteropus.

Pterpus tonganus.text: The parental care of Pterpus tonganus as not been well documented.

Ptilocercus.text: Because captive breeding has not been done with Ptilocercus, whether this strange parenting method characterizes the Pentail Tree Shrew is unknown.

Ptilocercus lowii.text: Very little life history work has been done on Ptilocercus lowii, as it is rare and difficult to capture (compared to other tupaiids).

Ptychobranchus fasciolaris.text: Michigan, Ptychobranchus fasciolaris was gravid from mid-August to mid-May.

Puffinus gravis.text: Puffinus gravis is a colonial nester, nesting in burrows or crevices among boulders along hilly island shores.

Pugettia producta.text: Pugettia producta undergoes a terminal molt upon reaching sexual maturity.

Pusa hispida.text: In their closest relatives, Pusa hispida, as well as other seal species, males leave females soon after mating and do not help raise the newborn pups.

Pycnopodia helianthoides.text: Pycnopodia helianthoides breeds by broadcast fertilization between March and July.

Pyganodon cataracta.text: The maximum amount of glochidia in one female is unknown, but Tankersley and Dimock (1992) recorded nearly 1 million in a Pyganodon cataracta female.

Pyganodon grandis.text: Michigan, Pyganodon grandis was gravid from early August to the following mid-April.

Pyganodon lacustris.text: Pyganodon lacustris is likely a long-term brooder and spawns in summer in Michigan. (Lefevre and Curtis, 1912; Watters, 1995)

Pygathrix nameaus.text: Although the lifespan of these monkeys has not been described, individuals in the related species, douc langurs (Pygathrix nameaus) are reported to have lived about 26 years in captivity. (Nowak, 1999)

Pygocentrus nattereri.text: Pygocentrus nattereri seems to have a type of courtship display that involves swimming in circles.

Pygoderma bilabiatum.text: Pygoderma bilabiatum - females have one offspring per pregnancy.

Pygoscelis papua.text: Pygoscelis papua are the least abundant of penguin species with a total breeding population of approximately 314,000 pairs. (Bost,1994)

Python molurus.text: Python molurus reaches sexual maturity between 2-3 years of age provided the proper body weight is met.

Quadrula pustulosa.text: We evaluated concentrations in sediments, mussels (Quadrula pustulosa and Q. metanevra), and fish (Percina phoxocephala, Cyprinus carpio, and Ictiobus bubalus) from three sites on the Neosho River and one site on the Cottonwood River.

Quadrula quadrula.text: Quadrula quadrula is probably a short term brooder, mating in early summer and releasing glochidia in late summer. (Lefevre and Curtis, 1912; Watters, 1995)

Quercus ilicifolia.text: Barton (1996) observed males flying low over vegetation then dropping down and presumably searching for females around the bases of blueberry bushes Vaccinium spp. and scrub oaks Quercus ilicifolia.

Quercus variablis.text: In China, Chinese red pine (Pinus massoniana) and Chinese cork oak (Quercus variablis) are both preferred nesting trees, although other trees have also been used.

R. a. aurora.text: The female lays egg masses (ranging from 2000 to 5000 eggs in R. a. draytonii and 500-1100 in R. a. aurora) in permanent bodies of water that contain extensive vegetation, consisting of cattails and tules or bulrushes growing in the water with a vertical orientation.

R. a. draytonii.text: The female lays egg masses (ranging from 2000 to 5000 eggs in R. a. draytonii and 500-1100 in R. a. aurora) in permanent bodies of water that contain extensive vegetation, consisting of cattails and tules or bulrushes growing in the water with a vertical orientation.

R. capensis.text: There is no good documentation on the life expectancy of R. capensis.

R. fulvorufula.text: Although no lifespan has been reported for R. fulvorufula, another species in the genus, R. redunca is reported to live as long as 18 years in captivity.

R. indica.text: Little is known of mating behavior in R. indica.

R. kipunji.text: There is no information on the approximate lifespan of R. kipunji.

R. niger.text: Both sexes of R. niger attend to the eggs during the period of incubation.

R. norvegicus.text: These three features have previously been described from comparisons of the two allelic forms of C kappa genes in R. norvegicus.

R. rabida.text: Reproduction in R. rabida is one of the most commonly debated and studied areas of the animal's behavior.

R. raphanurus.text: The trapping of an adult male, adult female and two juveniles in one trap in a short time period led to the hypothesis that R. raphanurus live in family groups, indicating that both male and female participate in care of young.

R. rattus.text: Because male members of R. rattus copulate with one female and then move on to the next, they don't contribute much to the care of the young.

R. raviventris.text: It is not known if males of R. raviventris contribute to parental care.

R. redunca.text: Although no lifespan has been reported for R. fulvorufula, another species in the genus, R. redunca is reported to live as long as 18 years in captivity.

Rabidosa rabida.text: The larger, more fit Rabidosa rabida can live beyond two years in stable environments. (Comstock and Gertsch, 1965)

Ramphastos sulfuratus.text: The coloration is probably more of a camouflage in the brightly colored tropical regions where Ramphastos sulfuratus resides (Kricher, 1989; Beletsky, 1998).

Ramphastos swainsonii.text: Like many toucan species, Ramphastos swainsonii builds its nest in cavities in trees.

Ramphastos toco.text: Toco toucans (Ramphastos toco) live up to 20 years in captivity. (Busch Entertainment Corporation, 2002)

Rana areolata.text: Rana areolata breeds during the months from February to April, and it is sometimes seen breeding in large numbers.

Rana grylio.text: Wright speculates that Rana grylio may go through metamorphosis after one year.

Rana okaloosae.text: Rana okaloosae tadpoles overwinter and metamorphose the next spring or summer. (Moler, 1992)

Rana spenochephala.text: Rana spenochephala shows little to no parental investment in their offspring after laying an egg cluster.

Rana temporaria.text: Rana temporaria breeds in warmer lowlands in February & March and in the north and at high altitudes as late as June.

Rangifer tarandus.text: Even objects such as Rangifer tarandus bones are sometimes incorporated into nests.

Raphicerus campestris.text: Grysboks have lifespans similar to Raphicerus campestris. (Kingdon, 1982)

Raphicerus sharpei.text: Raphicerus sharpei can breed throughout the year.

Rattus argentiventer.text: Young Rattus argentiventer reach sexual maturity at 3 months.

Rattus norvegicus.text: Rattus norvegicus is capable of mating for up to two years. (Calhoun, 1962; Parker, 1990)

Rattus rattus.text: Rattus rattus tends to live for about a year in the wild with an annual mortality rate of 91 to 97%.

Ratufa bicolor.text: Gestation period in a close relative, Ratufa bicolor, was recorded to be 28 to 35 days in length.

Ratufa indica.text: Reproductive behavior of Ratufa indica is poorly known.

Ratufa macroura.text: Ratufa macroura are poorly studied and there is very little data available on their reproductive cycle.

Reithrodon auritus.text: The average lifespan of Reithrodon auritus in the wild is 3.7 months with a maximum longevity in the wild of about 15 months.

Reithrodontomys fulvescens.text: Peaks in reproduction for Reithrodontomys fulvescens occur in late spring and early autumn with a breeding season that extends from February all the way through to October.

Reithrodontomys megalotis.text: Reithrodontomys megalotis is known to undergo a post partum estrus cycle, allowing rapid production of litters.

Reithrodontomys montanus.text: Reithrodontomys montanus goes through 2 changes in pelage before reaching adulthood.

Reticulitermes flavipes.text: This causes their wings to fall off (Benavides, 1998) This flight is not considered a mating flight because Reticulitermes flavipes are only sexually attracted to their mates after their wings have broken off (Light, 1922).

Rhabdomys pumilio.text: For example, male four-striped grass mice (Rhabdomys pumilio) spend just as much time in the nest with their offspring as females do, grooming their young and retrieving them if they stray (Schradin and Pillay 2003).

Rhadinesthes decimus.text: We have no information about parental investment by Rhadinesthes decimus.

Rheobatrachus silus.text: In captivity, individual Rheobatrachus silus have lived up to 3 years.

Rhincodon typus.text: However, many believe that the embryo was aborted (and subsequently expelled from the mother's body), and that Rhincodon typus are viviparous.

Rhinoclemmys pulcherrima.text: Rhinoclemmys pulcherrima lays several clutches of three to five eggs from May to December.

Rhinoderma darwinii.text: Female Rhinoderma darwinii lay their eggs on moist soil and when the eggs hatch, the males "swallow" the tadpoles and put them in their specialized vocal sacs.

Rhinolophus capensis.text: Rhinolophus capensis are one of the many bat species that use delayed fertilization.

Rhinolophus eurylate.text: Given that the young are flying in July or August, it is likely that Rhinolophus eurylate is similar. (Nowak, 1999) In species of Rhinolophus for which data are available, lactation lasts for approximately one month.

Rhinolophus ferrumequinum.text: Lifespan/ Longevity: The oldest recorded age of an Rhinolophus ferrumequinum is 30 years (Schober and Grimmberger, 1997)

Rhinophylla pumilio.text: There is little available information on the parental involvement of Rhinophylla pumilio.

Rhodnius prolixus.text: Rhodnius prolixus lay eggs in a circadian rhythm that is influenced by light and dark cycles. (Ampleford and Davey, 1989; Roberts and Janovy, 2000)

Rhombomys opimus.text: Rhombomys opimus is gregarious and often individuals will burrow close to one another.

Rhynchocyon cirnei.text: Rhynchocyon cirnei breeds throughout the year.

Romanomermis culicivorax.text: Studies support cross-fertilization is the only mode of reproduction of Romanomermis culicivorax.

Rostrhamus sociabilis.text: North American examples of these species include Circus cyaneus and Rostrhamus sociabilis.

Rousettus aegyptiacus.text: Other bats from the same family, (Pteropus poliocephalis, Pteropus giganteus, and Rousettus aegyptiacus), recognize their young through vocalizations and olfaction.

Rucervus duvaucelii.text: The oldest captive Rucervus duvaucelii reached 23 years of age; in the wild, individuals typically reach 20 years old. (Huffman, 2006; Massicot, 2005)

Rungwecebus kipunji.text: A great deal of parental investment is characteristic of primates and the mother is generally the primary caregiver, so it is likely Rungwecebus kipunji shares these behaviors (McKenna, 1982; Simonds, 1974).

Rupicapra pyrenaica.text: The young of Rupicapra pyrenaica can usually follow their mothers almost immediately after birth, and they rapidly improve their leaping ability during the first few days of their life (Nowak, 1983).

Rynchops niger.text: Rynchops niger chicks are protected from overexposure to the elements by their parents.

S. aquaticus.text: Estrous behavior in unbred females follows a 12-day cycle, and estrus itself lasts about an hour in S. aquaticus.

S. arcticus.text: It is likely that S. arcticus is similar.

S. arizonae.text: Longevity of S. arizonae has not been reported.

S. attenuata.text: S. attenuata does not have any particular birthing season, although the number of births does rise in spring and autumn months.

S. bicolor.text: It is likely that S. bicolor is similar.

S. boliviensis.text: The breeding season for S. boliviensis is restricted to three months in length with estrus times averaging 7-8 days in length (Gibson,Kuehl, and Ruiz, 2005).

S. brasiliensis.text: No information was found on S. brasiliensis reproductive parental care.

S. calurus.text: Female S. calurus give birth to liters of three to five young in captivity, and two to three young in the wild.

S. celebensis.text: The lifespan of S. celebensis is unknown.

S. elegans.text: Parturition, which lasts approximately 95 minutes, occurs in late April to early May; the young of S. elegans appear above ground by late May or early June.

S. fulvivener.text: No information was found on mating systems for S. fulvivener.

S. fulviventer.text: Maximum lifespan/longevity for S. fulviventer is not known.

S. gaspensis.text: The life span of S. gaspensis is unknown, however, species from the genus Sorex typically live between one and two years.

S. glanis.text: The longest know lifespan in the wild is 80 years old for S. glanis.

S. graellsi.text: In the wild, the lifespan of S. graellsi is unknown, but in captivity they have lived 7 to 16 years.

S. hispidus.text: However, it is likely that what is known about reproduction in S. hispidus, the sister species of S. arizonae will apply reasonably well to the latter species. (Davis and Young, 1999)

S. hoyi.text: Because they are mammals, we know that S. hoyi females provide their young with milk.

S. insidiosus.text: There is little information on longevity in S. insidiosus.

S. murinus.text: Suncus varilla young stay with their mother for up to nine months after being weaned, whereas S. murinus young are separated from their parents within a few months. (Nowak, 1990)

S. poulsoni.text: Amblyopsidae, S. poulsoni are likely gill cavity brooders, like their kin.

S. richteri.text: Longevity in S. richteri is dependent upon caste.

S. saturatus.text: Individuals of S. saturatus are known to have lived at least 4 years in the wild.

S. sciureus.text: In S. sciureus, females are reported to show passive tolerance of males, and may even initiate some mating mounts.

S. spirula.text: The breeding patterns in S. spirula are unknown.

S. tenuis.text: Two close relatives, Sundasciurus lowii and S. tenuis, have litter sizes of 2 to 4.

S. townsendii.text: It is thought that S. townsendii has a ifespan similar to that of the closely related species, Scapanus orarius.

S. tundrensis.text: There is little specific information on reproduction in S. tundrensis.

S. v. melania.text: Young born to the subspecies S. v. melania have the characteristic dark color of the adult. (Best, 1995; Klein, 1977)

S. variegatoides.text: Little is known about parental investment in the species S. variegatoides.

S. variegatus.text: Very little is known about the lifespan of S. variegatus.

S. varilla.text: It is not known if its behavioral characteristics are similar to those of S. varilla. (Nowak, 1990)

Saccostomus campestris.text: Saccostomus campestris completes its breeding in the wet season so that the young are born when food will be readily available to the lactating mother and emerging juveniles.

Sagittarius serpentarius.text: The lifespan of Sagittarius serpentarius is currently unknown and further study is required.

Saguinus.text: The Genus Saguinus have specialized scent glands in the mid-chest region and in the area around the genitalia.

Saguinus geoffroyi.text: The life span of Saguinus geoffroyi is about 13 years (Grzimek, 1990,http://www.fsu.edu/~cppanama/ipsp/tamarin.htm, http://www.zoologi.su.se/personal/patrik/PrimData.htm, http://www.fsu.edu/~cppanama/ipsp/tamarin.htm, http://www.fsu.edu/~cppanama/ipsp/Tamarins.htm).

Saguinus oedipus.text: Electron microscopy of near-term placentas of two cottontop marmosets (Saguinus oedipus) revealed, in one placenta, the presence of budding and mature C-type virus particles associated with the basal trophoblast.

Saguinus fuscicollis.text: However, Saguinus fuscicollis breeds between April and October, and Saguinus oedipus and Saguinus geoffroyi breed between January and February.

Saguinus graellsi.text: Saguinus graellsi has a monogamous mating system and only the dominant female and dominant male mate.

Saguinus mystax.text: The reproduction of Saguinus mystax is perhaps its most interesting feature.

Saguinus nigricollis.text: Saguinus nigricollis has an average lifespan of 13.9 years in the wild (Rowe 1996).

Saguinus tripartitus.text: Saguinus tripartitus, like other Callitrichinae, live in groups in which only the dominant female mates.

Saimiri boliviensis.text: Saimiri boliviensis are polygynandrous creatures, meaning that both males and females in the troop may mate with multiple partners in a given breeding season.

Saimiri oerstedii.text: The birth rate in the genus Saimiri is about one birth per year (no information specifically for Saimiri oerstedii).

Saimiri sciureus.text: Although no data were available Saimiri oerstedii, females of its sister species Saimiri sciureus are in a period of estrous around 12 to 36 hours (Hayssen et al., 1993)

Salanoia concolor.text: However, a Salanoia concolor is reported to have lived only 4 years and 9 months.

Salmincola edwardsii.text: Male Salmincola edwardsii have the ability to mate with chalimus IV females of their same generation and with prior generations of unfertilized, adult females.

Salmonella tymphimurium.text: Limitations to lifespan include disease (for example Salmonella tymphimurium), parasitism, and sometimes exposure to cold temperatures.

Salpingotus crassicauda.text: Salpingotus crassicauda females have eight teats and have an average litter of 2.7 young.

Salvelinus confluentus.text: Salvelinus confluentus, whether in a lake or stream setting, become sexually mature between four and ten years old (Bjornn, 1991; USFWS, 1998).

Salvelinus namaycush.text: Because of the colder water habitats preferred by - Salvelinus namaycush -, fertilized eggs require a long time to hatch.

Sarcoramphus papa.text: The courting ritual of Sarcoramphus papa has only been observed in captivity; it is quite an elaborate show.

Sarotherodon galilaeus.text: Sarotherodon galilaeus, of northern Africa, Israel and Jordan, illustrate how distinctions between mating systems are blurred by a single pair of spawning cichlids.

Sarotherodon melanotheron.text: Sarotherodon melanotheron males nurture eggs and fry in the mouth for 15 days after spawning, while females are capable of spawning just a week later.

Scapanus orarius.text: It is thought that S. townsendii has a ifespan similar to that of the closely related species, Scapanus orarius.

Scapanus townsendii.text: Scapanus townsendii breeds once per year between November and February.

Scaphiopus bombifrons.text: Scaphiopus bombifrons - mates from May through August.

Scaphiopus couchii.text: Scaphiopus couchii (like other frogs and toads) breeds only during the warmer seasons of the year.

Scaridae.text: Polygyny is much more common than polyandry, and usually involves territorial males organized into harems (males breed exclusively with a group of females), as in numerous Cichlidae species and several families of reef fishes (Scaridae, Labridae and Pomacentridae, Malacanthidae, Acanthuridae and Balistidae). (Helfman, Collete, and Facey, 1997; Moyle and Cech, 2004)

Scarus croicensis.text: Jamaica Scarus croicensis emphasizes aspects of the foraging group system and spawning only takes place in groups.

Scarus vetula.text: Scarus vetula reproduce sexually with external fertilization.

Sceliphron.text: During the summer, female blue mud wasps build nests by bringing water to abandoned mud nests made by other species of wasps (mainly the genus Sceliphron).

Schistomatium douthitti.text: The life cycle of Schistomatium douthitti is quite complex.

Schistosoma mansoni.text: There is also a sporocyst stage in the larval stage of the life cycle of Schistosoma mansoni, which allows it to produce a very large quantity of offspring from a single zygote.

Scirtopoda telum.text: Lifespan has not been recorded for P. ctenodactylus, but two other species of jerboa, Scirtopoda telum, the thick tailed three toed jerboa, and Allactaga sibirica, the jumper jerboa, have both been observed to live around 2 years in the wild.

Sciurus.text: In Sciurus, gestation lasts between 33-46 days.

Sciurus carolinensis.text: However, their close relative, eastern gray squirrels (Sciurus carolinensis) are seasonal breeders; their mating activities are triggered by changes in day length and their productivity is linked strongly to food supply.

Sciurus griseus.text: When Sciurus griseus is approximately one year old it will begin breeding.

Sciurus oculatus.text: No studies have determined the average lifespan for Sciurus oculatus.

Scomber scombrus.text: Some, like Scomber scombrus (Scomber scombrus), spawn all summer long.

Scopus umbretta.text: Parents will sometimes inadvertently care for birds from other nests, including the young of black eagles (Ictinaetus malayensis) and hamerkops (Scopus umbretta). ("Storks (Ciconiidae)", 2003; Campbell, 1974; Perring and Middleton, 1985; Thompson, 1964)

Scutigera coleoptrata.text: Scutigera coleoptrata is stimulated by pheromones and sound signals.

Scyliorhinus canicula.text: We have studied the cardiac development of the dogfish (Scyliorhinus canicula) in six serially sectioned embryos ranging from 14 to 40 mm in total length.

Scyliorhinus retifer.text: There is no data regarding the lifespan of Scyliorhinus retifer, although certain captive Scyliorhinus retifer were at least nine years old at time of writing. (Castro, Overstrom, and Bubucis, 1988)

Scyllaea pelagica.text: Scyllaea pelagica is hermaphroditic, but cross-fertilizes through reciprocal copulation.

Sebastes aleutianus.text: Several species of rockfish (Sebastes mentella, Sebastes aleutianus and Sebastes aleutianus) live from 90 to 140 years!

Sebastes mentella.text: Several species of rockfish (Sebastes mentella, Sebastes aleutianus and Sebastes aleutianus) live from 90 to 140 years!

Seiurus aurocapillus.text: The nest of Seiurus aurocapillus is built in the open, on leaf-covered floor of deciduous woods or just above the ground in a clump of low plants or shrubs.

Sekeetamys calurus.text: Sexual maturity for Sekeetamys calurus is sixty to eighty days after birth.

Semibalanus balanoides.text: Semibalanus balanoides are hermaphrodites that reproduce by internal fertilization.

Semnopithecus entellus.text: While parental care of the offspring has not been observed for golden langurs, it is presumed to be similar to that of Semnopithecus entellus.

Serinus mozambicus.text: Serinus mozambicus breeds through the rainy season when there are sufficient food supplies to rear young.

Echinops telfairi.text: By day 25, both species are weaned; adulthood is reached by day 40 (maturity in other spiny tenrec species [Setifer setsosus and Echinops telfairi] doesn’t occur for 6 months).

Setifer setsosus.text: By day 25, both species are weaned; adulthood is reached by day 40 (maturity in other spiny tenrec species [Setifer setsosus and Echinops telfairi] doesn’t occur for 6 months).

Sialia mexicana.text: Juvenile helpers are much more common among Sialia mexicana. (Gowaty and Plissner, 1998)

Siganus rivulatus.text: Siganids characteristically school in small to large groups, with some species, such as Siganus rivulatus and Siganus luridus, breaking off into pairs or small units after spawning begins.

Siganus luridus.text: Siganids characteristically school in small to large groups, with some species, such as Siganus rivulatus and Siganus luridus, breaking off into pairs or small units after spawning begins.

Siganus vulpinus.text: Other members of the Siganidae family, such as the Siganus vulpinus, form monogamous pairs.

Sigmodon fulviventer.text: Sigmodon fulviventer constructs a nest woven out of grasses in which it resides and cares for their young.

Sigmodon hispidus.text: Sigmodon hispidus is known to undergo a postpartum estrus.

Simpsonaias ambigua.text: Simpsonaias ambigua is probably a long-term brooder, spawning in the summer and retaining glochidia until the following spring. (Lefevre and Curtis, 1912; Oesch, 1984; Watters, 1995)

Sinea diadema.text: Although no direct information was available, Sinea diadema emerges in the spring as an adult after having been in hibernation through the winter season.

Siren intermedia.text: The courtship behavior of Siren intermedia has not yet been described.

Siren lacertina.text: Little research has been done regarding Siren lacertina reproduction.

Sistrurus miliarius.text: Sistrurus miliarius are oviparous (live bearing) and usually give birth during the month of August.

Sminthopsis longicaudata.text: There is no information on reproduction in -Sminthopsis longicaudata- in the wild, but some studies have been performed on captive animals (Wooley and Valente 1986).

Sminthopsis macroura.text: The following information was also obtained from captive colonies; it is not known from wild Sminthopsis macroura.

Solenodon.text: Solenodon are relatively long lived animals.

Solenodon paradoxus.text: Very little is known about the reproductive behavior of Solenodon paradoxus.

Solenostomos paradoxus.text: In Solenostomos paradoxus, these cells occur only on the inside surface of the pelvic fins of females (the brooders in this species.

Solenostomus paradoxus.text: Solenostomus paradoxus is an external skin-brooding species.

Somniosus microcephalus.text: No specific information about the longevity of Somniosus microcephalus exists.

Sorex araneus.text: Sorex araneus can live for about 2 years.

Sorex cinereus.text: The breeding season for Sorex cinereus occurs from April to October in eastern North America but may extend into November if food is plentiful.

Sorex dispar.text: The reproductive season for Sorex dispar is between April through August and they usually have several litters throughout each year.

Sotalia fluviatilis.text: Whistles of boto, Inia geoffrensis, and tucuxi, Sotalia fluviatilis.

Sousa teuszii.text: Sousa teuszii has not been thoroughly studied.

Spalacopus cyanus.text: Based on colony age and sex ratios, the mating system of Spalacopus cyanus is likely polygynous, with males dispersing earlier than females.

Spalax ehrenbergi.text: Spalax ehrenbergi mating behavior is categorized into three stages: agonistic, courtship, and copulation.

Spea bombifrons.text: Spea bombifrons has been observed calling at mating ponds at temperatures as low as 10.5°C. (Alberta Government, 2002; Cannatella and Bockstanz, 1999; Farrar and Hey, 2006; Lauzon, 1999; Sargeant et al., 1993)

Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni.text: The lifespan of Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni is estimated at 5 to 10 years if they survive to adult size. (Kuhajda and Mayden, 2001; Romero, 1998)

Speothos venaticus.text: Speothos venaticus is most likely a monogamous species. Captive observations have indicated that Speothos venaticus groups form dominance heirarchies and can exhibit aseasonal reproduction patterns based on social interactions (Nowak 1999).

Spermophilus beecheyi.text: Young Spermophilus beecheyi may open their eyes at around 5 weeks of age.

Spermophilus beldingi.text: Spermophilus beldingi reaches sexual maturity at approximately 2 years.

Spermophilus brunneus.text: Spermophilus brunneus is very unique in that it shows sexual behavior for at least 12 to 13 days before mating.

Spermophilus lateralis.text: We have studied the ultrastructure of Sertoli-cell processes that extend into developing germ cells of the ground squirrel (Spermophilus lateralis).

Spermophilus mexicanus.text: Unlike many other species of scuirids, Spermophilus mexicanus only produces one litter per year (Lawlor 1979; Walker 1975).

Spermophilus parryii.text: Spermophilus parryii live in colonies of 5 to 50 members.

Spermophilus saturatus.text: Spermophilus saturatus is not known to store food.

Spermophilus spilosoma.text: The gestation period for Spermophilus spilosoma is 24 days (Sumrell 1949).

Spermophilus tereticaudus.text: The breeding season of Spermophilus tereticaudus starts in mid January with the enlargement of the male's testes.

Spermophilus washingtoni.text: Spermophilus washingtoni reaches sexual maturity early and first breed as yearlings (Verts and Carraway, 1998). In 1941, T. P.putida.text: The entry of fructose into P.putida cells appears to be mediated also by the glucose-gluconate uptake system, as shown by the ability to accumulate fructose of wild type cells grown on glucose, a substrate that induces the glucose-gluconate uptake system but not the fructose uptake system.

A. chrocococcum.text: By adding 99 Mo-molybdate to a cell culture of A. chrocococcum with nitrate as the nitrogen source, it has been possible to incroporate the radioactive metal into a purified preparation of the enzyme nitrate reductase.

Polygonum viviparum.text: Bulbils of Polygonum viviparum L. were a good source of metabolizable energy, protein and phosphorus, but were deficient in sodium.

Vaccinium myrtillus.text: Berries of Vaccinium myrtillus L. were the most digestible of the three foods, contained enough protein and P for maintenance, but were probably deficient in Na.

Gazella thomsonii.text: With the pelleted diets, the N content of the faecal dry matter (DM) was low for eland (Taurotragus oryx Pallas), high for sheep and cattle (Bos taurus and Bos indicus) and intermediate for the three small antelope species (hartebeest (Alcelaphus buselaphus cokei G√ºnther), Thomson's gazelle (Gazella thomsonii G√ºnther) and duiker (Sylvicapra grimmia L.)).

Thermoplasma acidophila.text: Plasma membranes were isolated from Thermoplasma acidophila, a mycoplasma-like organism which grows optimally at pH 2 and 59 degrees.

Penicillium notatum.text: With yeast extract as the carbon source (5 g/liter) and ammonium nitrate (1 g/liter) as the nitrogen source, both Rhizopus arrhizus and Penicillium notatum degraded the insecticide to a larger extent than with any other combination of nutrients used.

R. arrhizus.text: The optimum conditions for the degradation of the insecticide by R. arrhizus were observed at pH 6.0 to 7.0 and at 15-25 degrees C. Aged fungal mycelia were as active as mycelia in the logarithmic growth phase.

C. fulvus.text: The location of cellulase in C. fulvus depends on the carbon source for growth and the age of the culture.

Thiobacillus acidophilus.text: Thiobacillus acidophilus possesses the key enzymes of the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle including NAD-and NADP-linked isocitric dehydrogenase and alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase, and the key enzymes of the hexose monophosphate pathway (glucose-6-phosphate and 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase, and fructose 1,6-diphosphate aldolase).

Hitosplasma capsulatum.text: A mediastinal mass of clinically undetermined nature was found at autopsy to be an enormous abcess due to secondary infection in granulamatous caseating mediastinal nodes caused by Hitosplasma capsulatum.

Scilla sibirica.text: For the first time the new pentaploid chromosome race with 2n=30 was found in Scilla sibirica.

Sphaerodema annulatum.text: Unlike many heteropterans, the retrocerebral endocrine organs of the water-bug, Sphaerodema annulatum are not fused with each other or with the hypocerebral ganglion.

Acanthophtalmus kuhlii.text: [Nuclear function during early development of remote fish hybrids]The participation of paternal genome was studied in the development of remote hybrids obtained as a result of artificial insemination of the loach (Misgurnus fossilis) eggs by the sperm of aquarial Cyprinids (Brachydanio rerio, Danio malabaricus, Barbus tetrazona, Razbora heteromorpha, Carassius auratus) and Cobitids (Acanthophtalmus kuhlii).

A. africanus.text: In the A. africanus to H. sapiens lineage, cranial capacity increases with positive allometry (slope 1.73) while cheek teeth decrease absolutely (slope - 0.725).

H. habilis.text: The one early hominid to show a significant departure from this adaptive pattern toward later hominids-cranially, dentally, and postcranially-is H. habilis from East Africa.

Peromyscus maniculatus bairdi.text: Sibling mating in prairie deer mice (Peromyscus maniculatus bairdi) results in poor reproductive performance.

Asperguillus fumigatus.text: Late asthmatic reactions to inhalation of fractions from extracts of Candida albicans and Asperguillus fumigatus.

C.albicans.text: Taking the results to animal experiments into consideration it would appear that some of the late responses after exposure to Prot or crude extract of C.albicans and A.fumigatus were due to allergic mechanism of the delayed type.

Providencia stuartii.text: Proteus rettgeri and Providencia stuartii were notably more susceptible to verdamicin.

P. stuartii.text: The resistance of P. stuartii to all currently used antibiotics allows the utilization of this technique in the presence of other concurrently administered antibiotics and therefore eliminates the need for their inactivation in the assay procedure.

Penicillium avellaneum.text: A quantitative microbiological assay and a bioautography system with Penicillium avellaneum UC-4376 was developed for the antitumor drugs maytansine, and its homologues, maytanprine and maytanbutine.

C. ramosum.text: Results showed that, among the anaerobes, C. ramosum is second only to Bacteroides fragilis in its resistance to antimicrobial agents.

P. boryanum.text: Deoxyribonucleic acid synthesis was blocked virtually without delay by virginiamycin M. Since virginiamycin inhibited protein synthesis in a similar fashion in the unicellular Anacystis nidulans, as well as in the filamentous P. boryanum, the mechanism of action of this antibiotic is probably the same in all blue-green algae.

B. fragilis subsp.text: In order to determine the therapeutic value of penicillins in the management of anaerobic infections caused by Bacteroides fragilis, the antibacterial activity of penicillin G, ampicillin, and carbenicillin against 10 strains of B. fragilis subsp.

Cephalosporium acremonium.text: A number of Cephalosporium acremonium mutants blocked in the synthesis of cephalosporin C were investigated for accumulation of other beta-lactam compounds.

Elatobium abietinum.text: Laboratory investigations into the low-temperature tolerance of the green spruce aphid, Elatobium abietinum, revealed that the insect was killed by freezing.
